const QUESTIONS = [
{id:1,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define observations and variables",q:"A hospital database has one row per patient and columns for age, diagnosis, and length of stay. Each row is called a(n):",opts:["Variable","Feature","Observation","Target"],ans:2,exp:"Each row represents a single subject and is called an observation (or record). Variables are the columns — specific attributes recorded for every observation."},
{id:2,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify target vs predictor variables",q:"An insurer predicts annual claim cost. The dataset has age, vehicle type, region, and claim cost. Which is the target variable?",opts:["Age","Vehicle type","Region","Claim cost"],ans:3,exp:"The target variable is what the model predicts. Claim cost is the outcome of interest; age, vehicle type, and region are predictors used to explain variation in it."},
{id:3,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Classify variable types",q:"Which is best classified as a count variable?",opts:["Body temperature in Celsius","Number of hospital readmissions","Blood type (A, B, AB, O)","Annual salary"],ans:1,exp:"Count variables record discrete non-negative integers. Number of readmissions counts how many times an event occurred. Temperature and salary are continuous; blood type is a factor."},
{id:4,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Classify variable types",q:"Policy type recorded as Auto, Home, or Life is an example of which variable type?",opts:["Continuous","Count","Factor","Binary"],ans:2,exp:"A factor records categories or levels. Policy type with three distinct categories is a factor. Binary variables are a special case with exactly two levels."},
{id:5,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Distinguish regression from classification",q:"An actuary models whether a policyholder will renew their policy (Yes/No). This is:",opts:["Regression because the target is financial","Classification because the target is binary categorical","Supervised only if dataset exceeds 1000 rows","Unsupervised because no transformation is needed"],ans:1,exp:"Classification problems have categorical targets. A binary Yes/No outcome is categorical. Regression problems have continuous or count targets."},
{id:6,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define supervised vs unsupervised learning",q:"Which characteristic distinguishes supervised from unsupervised learning?",opts:["Supervised requires 10000+ observations","Supervised uses a labelled target variable; unsupervised does not","Supervised always produces better predictions","Supervised cannot handle factor variables"],ans:1,exp:"Supervised learning requires a labelled target variable the model learns to predict. Unsupervised learning analyzes patterns without any target variable."},
{id:7,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Interpret the random component",q:"In Y = f(X) + epsilon, what does epsilon represent?",opts:["Predicted value","Systematic component — the mean","Random component — unexplained variation around the mean","Coefficient estimates from OLS"],ans:2,exp:"Epsilon is the error term — the unexplained variation in the target after accounting for predictors. It is the noise in the signal-plus-noise decomposition of the target."},
{id:8,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Distinguish variables from features",q:"An analyst calculates age_at_policy_start from date_of_birth for modeling. How should age_at_policy_start be classified?",opts:["Target variable","Variable in original recorded form","Feature — a derived predictor created with deliberate thought","Observation"],ans:2,exp:"Features are predictors derived from the dataset with thought put into them and deemed suitable for modeling. Age_at_policy_start required deliberate calculation — that distinguishes a feature from a raw variable."},
{id:9,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain target leakage",q:"A loan default model includes missed_payments_this_year. Why is this problematic?",opts:["Variable is right-skewed","Target leakage — future information unavailable at prediction time for new applicants","Must be binarized before use","Creates multicollinearity with credit score"],ans:1,exp:"Target leakage occurs when a predictor contains information about the target unavailable at prediction time. Missed payments this year don't exist for new applicants — future information. Models with leakage fail in deployment."},
{id:10,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify target leakage",q:"A fraud model includes refund_amount_requested_after_claim. What concern does this raise?",opts:["Variable needs log transformation","Target leakage: refund requests happen after the fraud decision and would be unavailable at real prediction time","Multicollinearity with claim amount","Heteroscedasticity violation"],ans:1,exp:"If refund requests occur after fraud investigation, this variable contains future information unavailable at real prediction time. It's target leakage — a critical flaw that causes deployment failure."},
{id:11,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Use correct terminology",q:"A junior analyst says he uses age, income, and health score as observations to predict hospitalization cost. What is wrong?",opts:["Nothing is wrong","Age, income, and health score are predictor variables not observations; observations are rows (individual subjects)","Hospitalization cost should be a predictor","Should say independent variables instead of observations"],ans:1,exp:"Observations are the rows — each representing a single subject. Age, income, and health score are predictor variables (columns). Confusing observations with variables leads to imprecise communication."},
{id:12,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply systematic vs random component",q:"A model estimates a 25-year-old male's expected claim frequency as 0.15 per year. He actually filed 3 claims. The 3 claims represent:",opts:["Only the systematic component","Only the random component","Both: 0.15 is systematic, deviation from 0.15 is random","Neither"],ans:2,exp:"Target = systematic + random. The systematic component is 0.15 (model's expected mean). The actual 3 claims contain both the systematic (0.15) and a large random component (2.85 deviation)."},
{id:13,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Hard",lo:"Classify edge case variable types",q:"Customer satisfaction rated 1-5 where each number is a distinct opinion category. How should this be treated?",opts:["Always continuous since values are numeric integers","Always factor since values represent categories","Judgment call — both interpretations have merit and affect modeling behavior","Count variable recording how many times the customer was satisfied"],ans:2,exp:"This is a genuine judgment call covered in the manual. Treating as numeric assumes equal spacing; treating as factor estimates separate effects per level. Neither is universally correct — context and model behavior should guide the choice."},
{id:14,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Hard",lo:"Distinguish parametric vs non-parametric methods",q:"Which best describes the parametric vs non-parametric modeling tradeoff?",opts:["Parametric always more accurate than non-parametric","Parametric assumes a functional form enabling interpretable coefficients but risks misspecification; non-parametric is more flexible but harder to interpret","Non-parametric always outperforms parametric on large datasets","Parametric only suitable for continuous target variables"],ans:1,exp:"Parametric methods assume a fixed functional form and estimate parameters — interpretable but risks misspecification. Non-parametric methods discover structure from data — flexible but harder to interpret and more prone to overfitting."},
{id:15,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate when predictive modeling is appropriate",q:"A company wants to forecast claims for a product launched 6 months ago. Which condition most strongly argues against predictive modeling?",opts:["Cannot handle insurance data","Target is continuous requiring regression approach","Insufficient historical data makes a reliable model impossible","Model cannot be explained to regulators"],ans:2,exp:"The manual's checklist requires relevant data to be available. With only 6 months of data for a new product, insufficient history exists to identify stable patterns. Traditional actuarial approaches may be more appropriate."},
{id:16,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define data organization terms",q:"In a dataset stored as a table, what does each column represent?",opts:["Observation containing all data for one subject","Variable representing a specific attribute measured for every subject","Record combining related observations","Target containing the outcome of interest"],ans:1,exp:"Each column is a variable — a specific attribute measured or recorded for every observation. This is standard tidy data organization used throughout predictive analytics."},
{id:17,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify continuous variables",q:"Which is best classified as a continuous variable?",opts:["Number of children in a household","Customer satisfaction 1-5 treated as categories","Body weight in kilograms","Credit rating (A, B, C)"],ans:2,exp:"A continuous variable measures a quantity that can take any value within an interval. Body weight can be any positive real number. Number of children is a count; satisfaction as categories is a factor; credit rating is a factor."},
{id:18,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand target type implications",q:"An analyst predicts annual premium revenue per policyholder: positive, continuous, right-skewed. What does this target nature most directly suggest about modeling?",opts:["Logistic regression appropriate because target is bounded","MLR may be unsuitable due to skewed positive-only nature; a Gamma GLM may be better","Decision tree cannot be used because target is continuous","Target must be log-transformed before any analysis"],ans:1,exp:"Premium revenue is continuous, positive, and right-skewed — characteristics matching the Gamma distribution in GLM. MLR assumes a normal target, which is inappropriate here. Model selection should reflect the target's distributional nature."},
{id:19,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Recognize regression vs classification",q:"Which goal corresponds to a regression problem?",opts:["Predicting whether a patient will be readmitted within 30 days","Predicting the probability that a loan will default","Predicting total claims cost filed by a policyholder next year","Classifying customers as high, medium, or low risk"],ans:2,exp:"Regression problems have continuous or count targets. Total claims cost is continuous. The other options involve categorical or binary outcomes, making them classification problems."},
{id:20,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate variable type misidentification in R",q:"Region is stored as integers 1,2,3,4 in R. An analyst fits MLR without converting to factor. What is the consequence?",opts:["Model will crash — MLR cannot handle integers","Model treats region as continuous, incorrectly assuming equal spacing and linear trend across regions","Model automatically creates dummy variables","Model only uses observations where region equals 1"],ans:1,exp:"R treats integer variables as numeric unless converted to factors. Using region as numeric forces a single slope coefficient assuming 1 to 2 to 3 to 4 is a linear progression — almost certainly wrong for geographic regions. Converting to factor creates separate coefficients per level."},
{id:21,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define the null model",q:"In MLR context, what is the null model?",opts:["Model with all available predictors included","Model with only an intercept and no predictor variables","Model where all coefficients including intercept are set to zero","Model that produces predictions equal to zero"],ans:1,exp:"The null model contains only an intercept (beta-naught) and no predictor variables. It predicts the training mean for every observation and serves as the baseline for F-tests and AIC/BIC comparisons."},
{id:22,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand holding other predictors constant",q:"MLR: Salary = 30000 + 2500 times YearsExp + 5000 times HasMBA. The coefficient 2500 for YearsExp means:",opts:["Each year raises salary by 2500 regardless of all other factors in reality","Holding MBA status constant, each additional year of experience is associated with a 2500 increase in predicted salary","Average salary for one year of experience is 32500","Years of experience more important than MBA since 2500 vs 5000"],ans:1,exp:"MLR coefficients are interpreted holding all other predictors constant (ceteris paribus). The coefficient 2500 means: for two individuals with the same MBA status, the one with one more year of experience is predicted to earn 2500 more. This holding-constant qualification is essential."},
{id:23,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify factor variables",q:"Education recorded as High School, Bachelor's, Master's, or PhD is:",opts:["Continuous because education is on a scale","Count because it counts years of education","Factor because it records distinct categories","Binary because it can be converted to yes/no indicator"],ans:2,exp:"A factor records categories or levels. Education level has four distinct categories making it a factor. It is specifically ordinal since levels have a natural ordering."},
{id:24,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand training vs test sets",q:"A model is fitted on 70% of data and evaluated on 30%. What are these subsets called?",opts:["Training set and validation set","Fitting set and holdout set","Training set and test set","In-sample set and out-of-sample set"],ans:2,exp:"The 70% used to estimate model parameters is the training set. The 30% not used in fitting, which evaluates generalization to new observations, is the test set."},
{id:25,topic:"Data Fundamentals",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply signal-noise decomposition",q:"A claim frequency model has training RMSE of 0.02 and test RMSE of 0.31. What does this indicate?",opts:["Model correctly captured systematic component with minimal noise","Model captured random noise from training data that does not generalize","Test set is harder than training set","Random component in test set is larger than in training set"],ans:1,exp:"Very low training RMSE with high test RMSE is the hallmark of overfitting — the model learned training noise alongside the true signal. Noise is specific to training observations and does not generalize to new data."},
{id:26,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Easy",lo:"Describe random sampling",q:"In which sampling method does every record have equal probability of being selected without replacement?",opts:["Stratified sampling","Systematic sampling","Random sampling","Oversampling"],ans:2,exp:"Random sampling gives every record equal probability without replacement. It is the simplest method. Stratified sampling partitions data first; systematic sampling follows a pattern; oversampling is a special case of stratified sampling."},
{id:27,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify systematic sampling",q:"An analyst selects every 100th record from a database sorted by entry date. Which sampling method is this?",opts:["Random sampling","Stratified sampling","Systematic sampling","Cluster sampling"],ans:2,exp:"Systematic sampling draws records following a specific pattern or criterion. Selecting every 100th record is a systematic pattern. Unlike random sampling, not every subset has equal probability of selection."},
{id:28,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define oversampling",q:"A fraud dataset has 950 non-fraud and 50 fraud cases. After oversampling there are approximately 950 of each class. What was done?",opts:["950 non-fraud cases were randomly removed","50 fraud cases were deleted","Fraud cases were duplicated approximately 19 times to match non-fraud count","Analyst collected 900 additional real fraud cases"],ans:2,exp:"Oversampling duplicates minority class records to overcome having very few observations. With 50 fraud cases, duplicating each approximately 19 times yields roughly 950 fraud cases, balancing the dataset."},
{id:29,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define undersampling",q:"A dataset has 8000 negative and 2000 positive cases. After undersampling there are approximately 2000 of each class. What happened?",opts:["8000 negatives kept and 6000 positives added","6000 negative cases randomly removed to match the positive class size","2000 positive cases were duplicated","2000 positives were removed and replaced with negatives"],ans:1,exp:"Undersampling removes observations from the majority class until both classes are roughly equal. Here 6000 of 8000 negative cases were discarded, leaving 2000 negative to match 2000 positive."},
{id:30,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Know reasons for sampling",q:"Which is NOT listed as a reason for sampling data in the manual?",opts:["Managing dataset size","Addressing imbalanced data","Improving model interpretability","Facilitating model testing"],ans:2,exp:"The four reasons for sampling per the manual: managing dataset size, handling irrelevant or misleading data, addressing imbalanced data, and facilitating model testing. Improving model interpretability is not a reason for sampling."},
{id:31,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply sampling to imbalanced data",q:"A classification problem has 99% negative and 1% positive cases. Without rebalancing, what behavior is likely?",opts:["Perfectly balances sensitivity and specificity at 50%","Predicts positive for all observations achieving 1% accuracy","Predicts negative for nearly all observations achieving approximately 99% accuracy but near-zero sensitivity","Automatically weights minority class more heavily during training"],ans:2,exp:"With severely imbalanced data, a naive model achieves approximately 99% accuracy by predicting negative every time — never identifying positives. This gives high specificity but near-zero sensitivity. The high accuracy is misleading."},
{id:32,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Choose oversampling vs undersampling",q:"A dataset has 2000000 negative and 1000 positive cases. Which technique is most practical and why?",opts:["Oversampling because duplicating positives preserves all available data","Undersampling because even after removing most negatives the remaining dataset is still very large and usable","Both are equally practical — choice is arbitrary","Neither — imbalance is too severe to address"],ans:1,exp:"The manual states undersampling is handy when you have many many rows of data. With 2 million negatives, undersampling to approximately 1000 negatives still yields a 2000-row balanced training set sufficient for modeling and computationally manageable."},
{id:33,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply sampling in cross-validation",q:"During 5-fold cross-validation with imbalanced data, when should oversampling be applied?",opts:["To the entire dataset before creating folds","To each training fold separately not to the validation fold","To only the validation fold to simulate real-world conditions","After training is complete to the test set only"],ans:1,exp:"The manual explicitly states oversampling or undersampling should be applied to each training set (the k-1 folds) before fitting. Applying to the whole dataset before folding risks duplicated observations appearing in both training and validation sets, violating test set integrity."},
{id:34,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify oversampling drawbacks",q:"Which is a recognized drawback of oversampling the minority class?",opts:["Model cannot be evaluated on test set after oversampling","Model may overfit minority class because duplicate observations are created","Oversampling always results in lower AUC than undersampling","Majority class becomes too small to train on effectively"],ans:1,exp:"The manual notes oversampling can lead to overfitting the minority class since duplicates are created. The model sees identical minority observations repeatedly which can cause memorization of specific cases rather than generalizing the class's true pattern."},
{id:35,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Hard",lo:"Interpret sampling effects on model performance",q:"After undersampling, training accuracy drops from 97% to 78% but test accuracy improves from 61% to 74%. What does this suggest?",opts:["Undersampling worsened the model — training accuracy is the correct measure","Original model was overfitting the majority class; undersampling forced it to learn genuine patterns from both classes","The test set was corrupted during undersampling","The model needs more data — undersampling should be undone"],ans:1,exp:"The original model (97% training, 61% test) was overfitting — predicting majority class nearly always. Undersampling forced the model to encounter both classes equally, improving test accuracy from 61% to 74% despite lower training accuracy. The test improvement shows genuine generalization improvement."},
{id:36,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate oversampling on wrong data split",q:"An analyst applies oversampling to the full dataset (training plus test combined) before splitting into train and test sets. What specific problem does this create?",opts:["Model will have too many parameters","Some observations will appear in both training and test sets due to duplication, violating test set integrity","Factor variables will become imbalanced","Regularization penalty will be incorrectly calibrated"],ans:1,exp:"The manual explicitly warns against this. Oversampling creates duplicate records. Applied before splitting, the same original observation may appear in both training and test sets. This violates the test set definition making test metrics optimistically biased."},
{id:37,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand stratification",q:"Stratified sampling begins with which step before sampling records?",opts:["Sorting all records by the target variable","Partitioning the dataset into distinct groups or strata","Removing all records with missing values","Standardizing all numeric variables"],ans:1,exp:"Stratified sampling begins by partitioning the dataset into distinct groups or strata. Records are then independently and randomly sampled from each stratum. Oversampling and undersampling are special cases of stratified sampling."},
{id:38,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand purpose of test set",q:"Why is it important to have a separate test set not used during model training?",opts:["Test set is only needed for regularization methods","Separate test set provides unbiased estimate of how model generalizes to new unseen data","Used to update model coefficients after initial training","Required only when training set has fewer than 1000 observations"],ans:1,exp:"The test set contains observations not used to estimate parameters. Because the model never saw them, test RMSE provides an honest estimate of real-world performance. Training metrics are optimistically biased since the model was fitted to those observations."},
{id:39,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand sampling effects on probabilities",q:"After oversampling with 50% positives in training (true prevalence is 5%), what adjustment may be needed at deployment?",opts:["No adjustment needed — balanced training produces accurate real-world probabilities","Predicted probabilities may need recalibration since training class distribution differs from the real-world distribution","Model must be retrained on unbalanced data before deployment","Oversampled models can never be deployed"],ans:1,exp:"When training class distribution is artificially altered (5% to 50% positives), the model learns a prior differing from reality. Predicted probabilities for the minority class will be inflated. Recalibration (such as Platt scaling) may be needed to reflect true 5% prevalence."},
{id:40,topic:"Sampling",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply oversampling within CV folds",q:"During 10-fold CV for a fraud model, oversampling is applied to fold 3's training data with 90 genuine and 10 fraud cases. After oversampling the training set contains approximately:",opts:["90 genuine and 90 fraud cases (80 duplicated fraud plus 10 original)","90 genuine and 10 fraud cases (no change)","10 genuine and 10 fraud cases (after undersampling genuine)","100 genuine and 100 fraud cases (combining all folds)"],ans:0,exp:"Oversampling duplicates minority until classes are roughly equal. With 90 genuine and 10 fraud, duplicating 10 fraud cases 8 times each gives approximately 90 fraud. Total training set for fold 3 becomes approximately 180 observations."},
{id:41,topic:"EDA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define EDA",q:"Which phrase best captures the purpose of EDA from the manual?",opts:["Using models to make accurate predictions about future events","Investigating a dataset using numerical and graphical summaries","Estimating regression coefficients using ordinary least squares","Selecting the optimal link function for a GLM"],ans:1,exp:"The manual defines EDA as the investigation of a dataset using numerical and graphical summaries. Like watching highlights of a sports game, EDA helps quickly grasp key aspects before formal modeling begins."},
{id:42,topic:"EDA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify univariate numerical summaries",q:"Which is a univariate numerical summary?",opts:["Scatterplot showing relationship between two variables","Correlation between age and income","Mean of the target variable across all observations","Side-by-side boxplot of claims by region"],ans:2,exp:"Univariate analysis studies one variable at a time. The mean of the target is a univariate numerical summary. Correlations and scatterplots are bivariate; side-by-side boxplots by region combine target with a grouping factor."},
{id:43,topic:"EDA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Interpret mean vs median for skewness",q:"A variable has mean=8.4 and median=3.1. What does this indicate?",opts:["Left-skewed with long lower tail","Approximately symmetric around its center","Right-skewed with large values pulling mean above median","Variable has exactly one outlier equal to 8.4"],ans:2,exp:"Mean substantially greater than median indicates right skew. A few very large values pull the mean upward while the median stays near the bulk of the data. This rule of thumb is explicitly stated in the manual."},
{id:44,topic:"EDA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Interpret binary variable mean",q:"Binary variable fraud_flag (1=fraud, 0=legitimate) has mean=0.034. How is this interpreted?",opts:["The average fraud amount is $0.034","3.4% of transactions in the dataset are fraud","The model predicts 3.4% probability for all transactions","34% of transactions have fraud_flag near zero"],ans:1,exp:"The mean of a 0/1 binary variable equals the proportion of 1s. A mean of 0.034 means 3.4% of transactions are fraudulent. The manual explicitly illustrates this using hospital readmission data."},
{id:45,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Select appropriate EDA tool",q:"An analyst wants to visualize the distribution of a single continuous variable. Which EDA tool is most appropriate?",opts:["Correlation matrix","Histogram","Scatterplot","Confusion matrix"],ans:1,exp:"A histogram depicts the distribution of a numeric variable by dividing it into equal-length bins. Correlation matrices are for multivariate analysis; scatterplots are bivariate; confusion matrices evaluate classification model performance."},
{id:46,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Select bivariate EDA tool",q:"An analyst studies how a continuous target varies across levels of a 5-level factor. Which EDA tool is most appropriate?",opts:["Histogram of target variable alone","Scatterplot of target against a continuous predictor","Side-by-side boxplot of target grouped by factor levels","Correlation matrix of all numeric variables"],ans:2,exp:"Side-by-side boxplots are ideal for exploring the relationship between a continuous variable and a factor — showing the target distribution for each level of the factor simultaneously, enabling comparison across groups."},
{id:47,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify data errors using EDA",q:"During EDA of a US State variable, the analyst finds levels including Texas, California, Des Moines, and New York. What type of issue is present?",opts:["Skewness — variable needs log transformation","Class imbalance — Des Moines needs oversampling","Data error — Des Moines is a city not a state, indicating a recording error","Multicollinearity — Des Moines and New York are correlated with population"],ans:2,exp:"The manual uses exactly this type of example to illustrate data error detection. Des Moines is a city in Iowa, not a US state. EDA should catch such inconsistencies by reviewing all possible values of factor variables and checking against the data dictionary."},
{id:48,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret histogram for skewness",q:"A histogram of hospital days per stay shows a tall narrow bar at 1-2 days with very long low bars extending to 90+ days. What does this distribution shape indicate?",opts:["Left skew — most stays are long with a few very short","Symmetry — approximately bell-shaped","Right skew — most stays are short but a few are very long","Bimodality — two distinct groups of patients"],ans:2,exp:"A tall narrow bar near lower values with a long tail extending right is right skew. Most hospital stays are short (1-2 days) but a small number are very long, creating the rightward tail. Mean greater than Median in this distribution."},
{id:49,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Use correlation for bivariate analysis",q:"Correlation between years of experience and salary is computed as 0.73. How should this be interpreted?",opts:["A one-year increase in experience leads to $0.73 increase in salary","73% of variation in salary is explained by experience","There is a moderately strong positive linear relationship between experience and salary","Experience and salary are identical since correlation exceeds 0.5"],ans:2,exp:"Correlation measures the strength and direction of linear relationship between two variables. A value of 0.73 indicates a moderately strong positive linear association. It does NOT measure causation or equal the slope, and R-squared would be 0.73 squared = 0.53, not 0.73."},
{id:50,topic:"EDA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Identify limitations of correlation",q:"Correlation between age and premium is 0.05. Analyst concludes there is no relationship between the two variables. What is wrong with this conclusion?",opts:["Nothing — a correlation near zero confirms no relationship of any kind","Correlation only measures linear relationships; age and premium could have a strong non-linear U-shaped relationship","Correlation should be computed on standardized variables first","A correlation of 0.05 means 5% of variance is explained which is significant"],ans:1,exp:"Correlation measures only linear relationships. Age and insurance premium often have a U-shaped or complex non-linear relationship (young and elderly drivers pay more). Near-zero linear correlation does not rule out a strong non-linear relationship — a critical limitation the PA exam tests."},
{id:51,topic:"EDA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply EDA to identify transformations",q:"EDA of a loss cost variable shows extreme right skew and outliers above the 99th percentile that account for 40% of total loss. What should the analyst consider?",opts:["Remove the outliers permanently from the dataset","Apply log transformation and consider capping at a high percentile before modeling","Apply undersampling to remove excess small-loss observations","Convert loss cost to a binary variable indicating whether it exceeds the median"],ans:1,exp:"Log transformation compresses the long upper tail, making the distribution more symmetric and improving GLM stability. Capping (Winsorizing) extreme observations at a high percentile prevents a handful of catastrophic losses from dominating the model. Removing outliers entirely loses valuable information."},
{id:52,topic:"EDA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define bivariate analysis",q:"What is the defining characteristic of bivariate analysis in EDA?",opts:["Studies a single variable using multiple numerical summaries","Studies how a pair of variables behave together","Requires at least 1000 observations to be valid","Only applies when both variables are continuous"],ans:1,exp:"Bivariate analysis studies how a pair of variables behave together — particularly how the target variable relates to a predictor variable. Univariate analysis studies one variable in isolation."},
{id:53,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Select bivariate tools by variable types",q:"An analyst studies how a binary target (churned vs retained) relates to monthly spend (continuous). Which EDA approach is most appropriate?",opts:["Compute correlation between monthly spend and churn indicator","Create a scatterplot of monthly spend vs churn indicator","Create a stacked histogram or grouped boxplot of monthly spend divided by churn status","Fit a linear regression of spend on the churn indicator"],ans:2,exp:"When the target is binary and the predictor is continuous, a stacked histogram or grouped boxplot shows how the continuous variable's distribution differs across the two target classes — revealing whether churned and retained customers have different spend patterns."},
{id:54,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret numeric summary for skewness",q:"Age summary: Min=18, Q1=28, Median=41, Mean=46.3, Q3=57, Max=89. What does the relationship between median and mean suggest?",opts:["Left-skewed with more young people in the data","Right-skewed — some older individuals are pulling the mean above the median","Approximately symmetric — median and mean are close enough","Variable contains a data error since max age is 89"],ans:1,exp:"Mean (46.3) greater than Median (41) indicates right skew. Relatively few older individuals (up to age 89) pull the mean above the median. An age of 89 is plausible and not necessarily an error."},
{id:55,topic:"EDA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Detect data quality issues",q:"During EDA, the analyst checks the range of age and finds Min=-3, Max=112. What conclusions can be drawn and what actions should be taken?",opts:["Both values are plausible — ages from -3 to 112 are within normal ranges","Min=-3 is a clear error since negative ages are impossible; Max=112 warrants investigation but is not automatically wrong","Both indicate database corruption and the entire dataset should be discarded","The mean should be used instead of min and max for age validation"],ans:1,exp:"Negative ages are impossible — Min=-3 is a definitive data error. Max=112 is at the edge of plausibility and warrants investigation rather than automatic removal. The manual's guidance: check min and max of numeric variables for realistic values and investigate suspicious values using the data dictionary."},
{id:56,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand multivariate EDA tools",q:"A correlation matrix reveals predictors X1 and X2 have correlation=0.96. What concern does this raise for subsequent modeling?",opts:["Neither X1 nor X2 will be useful predictors because their target correlation must also be examined","Near-perfect correlation between X1 and X2 signals potential multicollinearity which could destabilize coefficient estimates in MLR","Both variables must be removed before any analysis can proceed","A correlation of 0.96 means one variable is a linear combination of the other and they are identical"],ans:1,exp:"High correlation between predictors signals multicollinearity — they contain overlapping information. In MLR, severe multicollinearity inflates standard errors of coefficients making individual estimates unstable and hard to interpret. The manual identifies this as a key concern to identify during EDA before modeling."},
{id:57,topic:"EDA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define quantiles",q:"The 75th percentile (Q3) of a variable is 12.4. What does this mean?",opts:["75% of observations have a value greater than 12.4","12.4 is the value that separates the bottom 75% of observations from the top 25%","75% of observations have a value exactly equal to 12.4","The variable's range extends from minimum to 12.4"],ans:1,exp:"The pth percentile is the value below which p% of observations fall. The 75th percentile of 12.4 means 75% of observations are at or below 12.4 and 25% are above. The median is the 50th percentile."},
{id:58,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Position EDA in the analysis pipeline",q:"At what point in the analysis pipeline does EDA typically occur relative to data cleaning and modeling?",opts:["EDA occurs after building the final model to validate assumptions","EDA occurs before data cleaning and modeling — it is used to identify issues and understand data first","EDA and modeling occur simultaneously in an iterative loop","EDA only occurs after data transformations are complete"],ans:1,exp:"EDA is described in the manual as occurring early — it is used to understand the dataset, identify data errors, detect outliers, and uncover relationships. Data cleaning typically occurs during or after EDA, and transformations follow. EDA informs what cleaning and transformations are needed."},
{id:59,topic:"EDA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate EDA output for model selection",q:"Target variable EDA reveals: mean=0, median=0.1, most values between -2 and 5, but 3% exceed 50, and 40% of observations are exactly 0. What do these features collectively suggest about model selection?",opts:["A normal distribution GLM is ideal because the mean is approximately 0","The data has excess zeros and a heavy right tail — a standard GLM may be insufficient; zero-inflated models or Tweedie distribution may be more appropriate","MLR is sufficient because the median is positive","The 3% extreme values should be removed before any modeling"],ans:1,exp:"A large mass of exact zeros combined with heavy right tail is classic in insurance loss data. Standard distributions cannot accommodate both simultaneously. Zero-inflated models or the Tweedie distribution that can handle exact zeros with a positive continuous tail are more appropriate choices."},
{id:60,topic:"EDA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret a boxplot for outlier detection",q:"A boxplot has IQR=10, Q1=20, Q3=30. Several observations appear as dots above 50 and below 5. How should these be interpreted?",opts:["They are rounding errors in the dataset","They are values more than 1.5 times IQR from the quartiles flagged as potential outliers requiring investigation","They indicate the variable is normally distributed","They represent missing values coded as extreme numbers"],ans:1,exp:"Boxplots use the 1.5 times IQR rule to flag potential outliers. With IQR=10, values above Q3+15=45 or below Q1-15=5 are plotted as individual dots. These are not automatically errors — they require investigation to determine if they are real extreme values or data entry mistakes."},
{id:61,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define the goal of data transformations",q:"What is the primary goal of data transformations in the predictive modeling workflow?",opts:["To replace the modeling step with pre-processed variables","To create variables from the existing dataset that may enhance its predictive value","To ensure all variables are normally distributed before analysis","To eliminate the need for EDA by cleaning data in advance"],ans:1,exp:"The manual defines data transformation as altering or converting variables with the primary goal of creating variables from the existing dataset that may enhance its value. Transformations occur after EDA and data cleaning but before modeling."},
{id:62,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Easy",lo:"Distinguish variables from features",q:"Which statement correctly distinguishes a variable from a feature?",opts:["A variable is always numeric; a feature is always categorical","A variable refers to data in its original recorded form; a feature is a derived predictor deemed suitable for modeling","A feature is a variable that has been standardized","Variables are used for EDA only; features are used for modeling only"],ans:1,exp:"The manual draws a deliberate distinction: a variable mostly refers to data in its original form. A feature has thought put into it — it is derived from the dataset and deemed suitable as a predictor. Features can be transformed variables or carefully selected original variables."},
{id:63,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Easy",lo:"Select appropriate transformation for right-skewed data",q:"A variable representing annual income has severe right skew with most values 20000-80000 but a long tail to 5000000. Which transformation is most appropriate for use in a GLM?",opts:["Standardize by subtracting mean and dividing by SD","Apply log transformation to compress the upper tail","Convert to binary: above vs below median income","No transformation needed — linear models handle all skewed variables automatically"],ans:1,exp:"Log transformation is the standard treatment for right-skewed positive variables. It compresses the long upper tail, making the distribution more symmetric and linearizing the relationship with the target. GLMs are not automatically robust to skewed predictors."},
{id:64,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Easy",lo:"Apply log transformation correctly with zeros",q:"A count variable number of prior claims has many zeros and right skew. An analyst applies log transformation directly. What is the problem?",opts:["Log transformation should only be applied to continuous variables not counts","log(0) is undefined (negative infinity) so the transformation fails for zero observations","Log transformation increases skew for count variables","Log transformation requires the variable to be standardized first"],ans:1,exp:"log(0) is mathematically undefined (negative infinity) as a real number. Applying log directly to a variable with zeros produces errors. The standard fix is to add a small constant first: log(x+1) ensures zero values become log(1)=0. The manual explicitly illustrates this using the absences variable."},
{id:65,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain standardization and when it is required",q:"Why is it crucial to standardize predictors before applying ridge, lasso, or elastic net regression?",opts:["Standardization makes the error term normally distributed satisfying GLM assumptions","Without standardization variables on larger scales receive larger penalties unfairly dominating the regularization","Standardization converts all variables to factors which regularization methods require","The regularization penalty becomes negative for unstandardized variables"],ans:1,exp:"Regularization methods penalize the magnitude of coefficients. A predictor measured in thousands will naturally have a smaller coefficient than one measured in single digits — not because it is less important but because of scale. Without standardization, the penalty disproportionately affects large-scale predictors. The manual states it is crucial to scale predictors before applying regularization."},
{id:66,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply dummy variable encoding",q:"A factor variable season has four levels: Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter. How many dummy variables are needed in a GLM and which level is excluded?",opts:["4 dummy variables — one per level","3 dummy variables — one level becomes the baseline excluded by default","2 dummy variables — one for each pair of seasons","Variable must first be converted to a numeric scale 1,2,3,4"],ans:1,exp:"For a factor with k levels, k-1 dummy variables are created (one level is excluded as the baseline). With 4 seasons, 3 dummy variables are created. The excluded level (e.g., Spring) serves as the baseline — its effect is captured in the intercept. All other coefficients measure the difference relative to Spring."},
{id:67,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain interaction terms and hierarchical principle",q:"An analyst wants to add an interaction between age (numeric) and region (factor) to an MLR model. The hierarchical principle requires that:",opts:["Only the interaction term is included; main effects are dropped to simplify the model","Both age and region main effects must also be included in the model alongside the interaction","The interaction must be binarized before inclusion","The analyst must first test each main effect individually with t-tests"],ans:1,exp:"The hierarchical principle states that if an interaction term is included, all lower-order terms involved in that interaction must also be present. Including age times region without age and region main effects forces those main effects' coefficients to be exactly zero — an unjustified constraint."},
{id:68,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify when to bin a numeric variable",q:"An analyst suspects age has a U-shaped relationship with claim cost (young and old drivers pay more). A GLM with continuous age fails to capture this. What transformation addresses it?",opts:["Log transform age to linearize the relationship","Standardize age so the coefficient is interpretable","Create age intervals such as under 25, 25-40, 41-60, 60+ and treat as factor allowing separate coefficient per band","Remove age since the relationship is non-linear"],ans:2,exp:"Creating factors of intervals (binning) allows the GLM to estimate a separate coefficient per age group, capturing non-monotone patterns like a U-shape. A log transformation still assumes a monotone relationship. A GLM with continuous age and log link cannot model the U-shape without additional terms."},
{id:69,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply polynomial transformation correctly",q:"An analyst includes x-cubed in an MLR model without including x or x-squared. What does the hierarchical principle say about this?",opts:["Acceptable since only the cubic term is needed","All lower-order terms x and x-squared must also be included — forcing their coefficients to zero without testing is unjustified","The cubic term must be standardized before inclusion","The model cannot contain both x-cubed and x due to multicollinearity"],ans:1,exp:"The hierarchical principle requires including all lower-order terms when higher-order terms are included. Including x-cubed without x and x-squared assumes their coefficients are exactly zero — a constraint that should be tested, not imposed by omission."},
{id:70,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate whether a transformation constitutes target leakage",q:"A model predicts whether a new customer will upgrade their subscription. A predictor upgrade_inquiry_flag indicates whether the customer called to ask about upgrading before the model makes its prediction. Is this target leakage?",opts:["Yes — customers who upgrade always make inquiries first so this encodes the outcome","No — the inquiry happens before the prediction time point so the information is available at prediction time","Yes — the inquiry is derived from internal CRM data which always constitutes leakage","No — leakage only occurs for financial variables"],ans:1,exp:"Target leakage occurs when a predictor contains information unavailable at prediction time. If the inquiry was made before the model runs (e.g., the model decides whether to proactively offer an upgrade), the flag is genuinely available at prediction time and is a legitimate predictor. The key question is always: was this information available when the prediction needs to be made?"},
{id:71,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Hard",lo:"Select appropriate transformation for model requirements",q:"A predictor household_income is highly right-skewed. After log transformation it becomes approximately symmetric. The analyst then standardizes the log-transformed variable before fitting lasso regression. What is the purpose of each transformation?",opts:["Log: removes skew and linearizes relationship with target. Standardize: ensures equal penalty treatment in lasso","Log: converts income to a count variable. Standardize: removes the intercept","Both transformations serve the same purpose and one is redundant","Log: required for Poisson regression. Standardize: required for logistic regression"],ans:0,exp:"Each transformation has a distinct purpose. Log transformation addresses skewness and typically linearizes the relationship with the target. Standardization ensures the lasso penalty is applied fairly across all predictors regardless of scale. Both are needed: log for the variable's distribution, standardization for the regularization penalty."},
{id:72,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Easy",lo:"Explain combining factor levels",q:"A vehicle brand variable has 40 levels. Many brands have fewer than 5 observations. Why might combining rare levels be beneficial?",opts:["To reduce the number of observations in the dataset","To eliminate multicollinearity between brand levels","To avoid unstable coefficient estimates for levels with very few observations and reduce model complexity","To convert the factor into a continuous variable for better model performance"],ans:2,exp:"Factor levels with very few observations produce unreliable coefficient estimates with large standard errors. Combining rare levels into an Other category produces a stable coefficient for the combined group, reduces model complexity (fewer parameters), and can improve generalization."},
{id:73,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand releveling factors",q:"An analyst relevels a factor so that the most common level becomes the baseline. What is the primary benefit?",opts:["The model AIC decreases when the most common level is the baseline","The intercept becomes more interpretable (representing a typical subject) and other coefficients represent deviations from the most common group","Releveling removes multicollinearity between dummy variables","The most common level always has the lowest coefficient and must be excluded"],ans:1,exp:"Choosing the most common level as baseline makes the intercept interpretable as a typical subject's baseline value since most observations belong to that group. Other coefficients represent differences relative to this common reference. There is no statistical reason to prefer one baseline — it is purely an interpretability choice."},
{id:74,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Medium",lo:"Create compound variables",q:"An analyst has number of injuries and employee hours worked as separate variables. They create injury_rate = injuries divided by employee_hours times 2000. This is an example of:",opts:["A dummy variable created by binarizing injuries","A compound variable combining multiple original variables into a single more meaningful predictor","A standardized variable with mean zero and SD one","Target leakage because injury rate uses information from the target variable"],ans:1,exp:"A compound variable is created by combining multiple original variables into a single variable that captures a more meaningful concept. Injury rate per 2000 hours normalizes raw injury counts by exposure (employee hours), creating a comparable rate across mines of different sizes. The manual uses exactly this example from the Mining Data task."},
{id:75,topic:"Data Transformation",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate transformation choices comprehensively",q:"A variable claim_amount has 60% of values exactly 0 (no claim filed) and remaining 40% are right-skewed positive values ranging up to 500000. Which approach is most comprehensive for modeling?",opts:["Apply log(claim_amount + 1) transformation to handle zeros and skew","Create a binary flag for non-zero claims AND model log(claim_amount) for positive claims separately in a two-part model","Standardize claim_amount to have mean 0 and SD 1","Bin claim_amount into 5 equal-width intervals"],ans:1,exp:"A two-part (hurdle) model is most appropriate for zero-inflated continuous data. Part 1: logistic regression predicts probability that claim is greater than 0. Part 2: conditional on a positive claim, a Gamma or log-normal GLM predicts log(claim_amount) for positive values. A single model cannot optimally capture both the zero mass and the right-skewed positive tail."},
{id:76,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify the five model groups in Exam PA",q:"Which of the following is NOT one of the five groups of models covered in Exam PA?",opts:["Multiple linear regression","Generalized linear models","Neural networks and deep learning","Ensemble decision tree models"],ans:2,exp:"The five model groups in Exam PA are: MLR, Stepwise Selection and Regularization, GLM, Single Decision Trees, and Ensemble Decision Trees. Neural networks and deep learning are not covered in the PA curriculum."},
{id:77,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Easy",lo:"Compute RMSE",q:"A model makes three predictions: predicted values are 10, 20, and 30; actual values are 12, 18, and 35. What is the approximate RMSE?",opts:["3.0","9.0","3.3","2.0"],ans:2,exp:"RMSE = sqrt(mean squared residuals). Residuals: (12-10)=2, (18-20)=-2, (35-30)=5. Squared residuals: 4, 4, 25. Mean squared: (4+4+25)/3 = 11. RMSE = sqrt(11) approximately 3.3."},
{id:78,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand training RMSE behavior",q:"As a model becomes more flexible, what happens to training RMSE?",opts:["It follows a U-shape decreasing then increasing","It increases monotonically — more complex models always have higher training error","It decreases monotonically — more flexible models always fit training data better","It stays constant regardless of model flexibility"],ans:2,exp:"Training RMSE always decreases (or stays the same) as model flexibility increases. More flexible models can fit training data more closely, eventually memorizing it. This is why training RMSE alone is a poor measure of model quality."},
{id:79,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify overfitting from RMSE patterns",q:"A model has training RMSE=0.15 and test RMSE=4.82. What does this indicate?",opts:["Model is underfit — too simple to capture patterns","Model is overfit — it memorized training data including noise that does not generalize","Test set is too small to provide a reliable estimate","Training and test sets must be from different populations"],ans:1,exp:"Near-zero training RMSE with very high test RMSE is the hallmark of overfitting. The model learned the training data so well (including random noise) that predictions generalize poorly to new observations. Underfitting shows high RMSE on both training and test sets."},
{id:80,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain bias-variance tradeoff",q:"A model with high bias and low variance is best described as:",opts:["Overfit — captures too much noise from training data","Underfit — makes strong simplifying assumptions and misses true patterns in the data","Well-calibrated — high bias and low variance is the ideal combination","Highly flexible — has many parameters relative to observations"],ans:1,exp:"High bias means the model systematically misses the true signal (too inflexible). Low variance means it gives similar predictions across different training sets (stable but wrong). This is underfitting. Overfitting = low bias, high variance."},
{id:81,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Medium",lo:"Describe cross-validation",q:"In k-fold cross-validation, how is the estimate of test error computed?",opts:["Model fitted once on all data; training error used as proxy for test error","Data split into k folds; model fitted on k-1 folds and evaluated on held-out fold, repeated k times, results averaged","Model fitted k times on random bootstrap samples and error computed on original data","Test error is computed as k times the training error"],ans:1,exp:"In k-fold CV: (1) data is split into k equal folds; (2) for each fold the model is trained on remaining k-1 folds and evaluated on held-out fold; (3) this produces k error estimates; (4) these are averaged. This provides a reliable estimate of generalization performance without requiring a separate test set."},
{id:82,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Medium",lo:"Compare parametric and non-parametric approaches",q:"Which statement best describes why non-parametric methods like decision trees do not require the same assumptions as MLR?",opts:["Non-parametric methods have no hyperparameters to tune","Non-parametric methods do not specify a fixed functional form — they discover the relationship from the data","Non-parametric methods always have lower test RMSE than parametric methods","Non-parametric methods cannot be overfit since they make no assumptions"],ans:1,exp:"Parametric methods like MLR specify the functional form in advance (linear relationship, normal errors) and estimate a fixed set of parameters. Non-parametric methods like decision trees impose minimal assumptions — they partition the predictor space in a data-driven way without assuming linearity or normality."},
{id:83,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Hard",lo:"Analyze test RMSE U-shape",q:"A model is trained with increasing numbers of predictors. Test RMSE initially decreases, reaches a minimum at 8 predictors, then increases. What explains the increase in test RMSE beyond 8 predictors?",opts:["Model requires more observations as predictors increase","Beyond 8 predictors the model fits noise specific to training data that does not generalize — variance increases","The predictors beyond 8 are factors which always increase test RMSE","More predictors always increase both training and test RMSE"],ans:1,exp:"The U-shaped test RMSE curve reflects the bias-variance tradeoff. Left side: adding predictors reduces bias (captures true signal), improving test RMSE. Minimum: optimal balance. Right side: additional predictors increase variance without reducing bias — the model captures training noise that does not generalize."},
{id:84,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate interpretability vs accuracy tradeoff",q:"An insurance regulator requires that premium factors be clearly explainable to policyholders. Which consideration most strongly influences model selection?",opts:["Predictive accuracy — always choose the model with lowest test RMSE","Interpretability — a GLM or MLR with clear coefficient interpretations may be preferred over a random forest even if test RMSE is slightly higher","Computational efficiency — fastest model should be selected","Data size — model requiring fewest observations should be used"],ans:1,exp:"The PA exam explicitly identifies interpretability as a key consideration. Regulators and policyholders require explainability. A GLM's coefficient for driver age can be stated as young drivers pay X% more — clear and defensible. A random forest's predictions emerge from thousands of trees and are difficult to justify to regulators."},
{id:85,topic:"Statistical Learning",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply k-fold CV to hyperparameter selection",q:"A data scientist uses 5-fold CV to select optimal depth for a decision tree. Results: depth 2 (CV error=0.45), depth 5 (CV error=0.32), depth 10 (CV error=0.33), depth 20 (CV error=0.41). Which depth is selected?",opts:["Depth 2, because simpler models generalize better","Depth 5, because it has the minimum cross-validation error","Depth 20, because deeper trees always capture more patterns","Depth 10, because it is between the extremes"],ans:1,exp:"The model with minimum cross-validation error is generally preferred. Depth 5 has the lowest CV error (0.32). The 1-SE rule might suggest depth 2 if depth 5's advantage is within measurement error — but without standard errors given, the minimum CV error at depth 5 is the standard selection."},
{id:86,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"State the MLR model equation",q:"The general form of a multiple linear regression model is:",opts:["Y = beta-0 + beta-1 times X1 + ... + beta-p times Xp + epsilon","Y = exp(beta-0 + beta-1 times X1 + ... + beta-p times Xp)","Y = beta-0 times X1 to the power beta-1 times Xp to the power beta-p","log(Y) = beta-0 + beta-1 times X1 + ... + beta-p times Xp"],ans:0,exp:"The MLR model is Y = beta-0 + beta-1 times X1 + ... + beta-p times Xp + epsilon. The systematic component models the mean of Y. The random component epsilon is normally distributed with mean 0 and constant variance (homoscedasticity)."},
{id:87,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define OLS estimation",q:"Ordinary least squares (OLS) estimates regression coefficients by:",opts:["Maximizing the R-squared value on the test set","Minimizing the sum of squared residuals on the training set","Maximizing the log-likelihood of the normal distribution","Minimizing the absolute sum of residuals"],ans:1,exp:"OLS finds coefficient estimates that minimize the error sum of squares (SSE) = sum of squared differences between observed and predicted target values across all training observations. It is not a test-set metric and does not use absolute residuals (that would be LAD regression)."},
{id:88,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"Interpret the intercept in MLR",q:"In an MLR predicting house price: Price = 50000 + 120 times SqFt + 15000 times HasGarage. The intercept 50000 means:",opts:["The model predicts $50000 for the average house","Every house has a base price of $50000 regardless of features","A house with zero square feet and no garage would be predicted to have a price of $50000","The model average error is $50000"],ans:2,exp:"The intercept is the predicted value of Y when ALL predictors equal zero. For a house with SqFt=0 and HasGarage=0, the model predicts $50000. Whether this is interpretable depends on context — a house with zero square feet is not physically meaningful, but the intercept retains its mathematical definition."},
{id:89,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"Interpret slope coefficients in MLR",q:"In an MLR predicting exam scores: Score = 45 + 3.2 times StudyHours minus 1.8 times Absences. How should the coefficient -1.8 be interpreted?",opts:["Each additional absence is associated with a 1.8-point decrease in predicted score holding study hours constant","Students with absences score 1.8 points lower than students with zero absences on average","The model prediction decreases by 1.8 for each unit increase in all predictors simultaneously","Absences reduces the intercept from 45 to 43.2"],ans:0,exp:"In MLR, each slope coefficient represents the change in predicted target for a one-unit increase in that predictor holding all other predictors constant. The -1.8 for absences means each additional absence is associated with a 1.8-point decrease in predicted score, after controlling for study hours."},
{id:90,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret dummy variable coefficients",q:"An MLR predicting salary includes a dummy variable IsMBA (1=has MBA, 0=no MBA) with coefficient 12000. The baseline is no MBA. How is this interpreted?",opts:["MBA holders earn exactly $12000 more than non-MBA holders in every case","On average MBA holders are predicted to earn $12000 more than non-MBA holders holding other predictors constant","$12000 is the salary for the average MBA holder","Obtaining an MBA increases salary by $12000 for every additional year of experience"],ans:1,exp:"A dummy variable coefficient represents the average difference in predicted target between the indicated level (MBA=1) and the baseline (MBA=0) holding all other predictors constant. The ceteris paribus qualification is essential — the coefficient controls for other variables like experience and industry."},
{id:91,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret interaction term coefficients",q:"An MLR model: Grade = 50 + 2 times Study + 5 times IsGP + 1.2 times (Study times IsGP). What does the interaction coefficient 1.2 mean?",opts:["Students at GP school who study get 1.2 points per hour on top of the base 2-point benefit per hour","For GP school students each additional study hour is associated with 2+1.2=3.2 points vs 2 points per hour for non-GP students","The average grade at GP school is 1.2 points higher than non-GP","Studying 1.2 hours is equivalent to attending GP school"],ans:1,exp:"Interaction terms modify the relationship between one predictor and the target based on another predictor. For non-GP students (IsGP=0) the study coefficient is 2 points per hour. For GP students (IsGP=1) the effective study coefficient is 2+1.2=3.2 points per hour. The interaction captures that studying is more beneficial at GP school."},
{id:92,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret the t-test for individual coefficients",q:"The p-value for a coefficient in an MLR model is 0.003. What does this indicate?",opts:["There is a 0.3% probability that the predictor is important","The predictor is statistically significant — strong evidence that the coefficient is non-zero","The coefficient is estimated with 99.7% accuracy","The model overall fit is adequate since the p-value is low"],ans:1,exp:"A small p-value (typically less than 0.05) in a t-test for an MLR coefficient provides strong evidence the coefficient is non-zero — the predictor has a statistically significant relationship with the target after controlling for other predictors. It does NOT measure practical importance or accuracy."},
{id:93,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret the F-test",q:"An F-test for an MLR model with 5 predictors has p-value=0.62. What does this suggest?",opts:["All 5 individual predictors are significant","The model with 5 predictors is significantly better than the null model","The data provides no strong evidence any predictor is useful — the model is not better than predicting the mean","The model is overfit and should be pruned"],ans:2,exp:"The F-test compares the fitted model (with all predictors) against the null model (intercept only). A large p-value (0.62 >> 0.05) indicates no strong evidence that any predictors collectively improve predictions over just using the mean. Different from individual t-tests — the F-test evaluates all predictors jointly."},
{id:94,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify MLR assumptions",q:"Which of the following is NOT one of the five MLR assumptions stated in the manual?",opts:["The error terms are normally distributed","The error terms have constant variance (homoscedasticity)","The predictor variables are uncorrelated with each other","No predictor is a linear combination of the other predictors"],ans:2,exp:"The five MLR assumptions: E(epsilon)=0, constant variance (homoscedasticity), independent errors, normally distributed errors, no predictor is a linear combination of others. The assumption is NOT that predictors are uncorrelated — mild correlation is acceptable; only perfect linear dependence violates the assumption."},
{id:95,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Diagnose violations from residual plots",q:"A residual-vs-fitted plot for an MLR model shows residuals randomly scattered for low fitted values but increasingly spread out (fan shape) for higher fitted values. Which assumption is violated?",opts:["Normality of errors — residuals not normally distributed","Independence of errors — observations are correlated","Homoscedasticity — variance of errors is not constant across fitted values","No multicollinearity — predictors are linearly related"],ans:2,exp:"A fan-shaped residual plot is the classic diagnostic for heteroscedasticity — violation of the constant variance assumption. Heteroscedasticity makes OLS standard errors incorrect, leading to unreliable t-tests and confidence intervals. A GLM with appropriate variance function can address this."},
{id:96,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Identify and address multicollinearity",q:"An MLR model includes both age_in_years and age_in_months as predictors. What problem does this create?",opts:["No problem — including more predictors always improves the model","Perfect multicollinearity — age_in_months is exactly 12 times age_in_years making one a linear combination of the other; OLS cannot uniquely estimate coefficients","Heteroscedasticity — the two age variables produce non-constant variance","Endogeneity — age in months causes age in years"],ans:1,exp:"Age in months = 12 times age in years — a perfect linear combination. This is perfect multicollinearity, violating the fifth MLR assumption. The OLS design matrix is singular and non-invertible, making it impossible to uniquely estimate coefficients. R will automatically drop one variable. Perfect multicollinearity arises from logical redundancy."},
{id:97,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply residual standard error interpretation",q:"An MLR for predicting exam scores has residual standard error (RSE) of 8.3 points. The mean exam score is 72 points. How should RSE be interpreted?",opts:["Model explains 8.3% of variation in exam scores","Average exam score prediction is off by exactly 8.3 points","RSE estimates sigma — the typical deviation of individual scores from their expected values; predictions are typically within about plus or minus 8.3 points","Model makes 8.3% of predictions incorrectly"],ans:2,exp:"The residual standard error estimates sigma, the standard deviation of the error term. It represents the typical magnitude of residuals — how far individual observations typically deviate from their predicted values. A RSE of 8.3 on a 0-100 scale with mean 72 means predictions are typically within roughly plus or minus 8.3 points."},
{id:98,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand R-squared and its limitations",q:"An MLR model has R-squared = 0.91. Which statement about this value is MOST accurate?",opts:["The model predicts new observations with 91% accuracy","91% of the variation in the target variable is explained by the predictors in the training set","The model will achieve 91% R-squared on the test set as well","The model is significantly better than one with R-squared of 0.85 in all scenarios"],ans:1,exp:"R-squared measures the proportion of training variance explained by the model. It does NOT guarantee test performance, does NOT measure prediction accuracy in absolute terms, and differences in R-squared may or may not be practically significant depending on context."},
{id:99,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply hierarchical principle in practice",q:"A model contains the interaction term income times education. According to the hierarchical principle, what must also be in the model?",opts:["Only income since it is more important","Only education since it modifies the income effect","Both income and education as separate main effect terms","Neither — interaction terms are self-contained"],ans:2,exp:"The hierarchical principle requires that when an interaction term is included, all lower-order terms involved must also be present. Both income and education must appear as main effects, even if their individual p-values are large. Omitting them forces those coefficients to be zero — an unjustified restriction."},
{id:100,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define R-squared",q:"R-squared in MLR is defined as the proportion of:",opts:["Observations correctly classified by the model","Total variance in the training target variable explained by the model","Residuals within one standard deviation of zero","Predictors that have statistically significant coefficients"],ans:1,exp:"R-squared = 1 minus SSE divided by SST, where SSE is error sum of squares (residual variance) and SST is total sum of squares (total variance). R-squared measures the proportion of total variance in the target explained by the model's predictors on the training set."},
{id:101,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret adjusted R-squared",q:"Adding a predictor to an MLR model increases R-squared from 0.72 to 0.725 but decreases adjusted R-squared from 0.71 to 0.708. What does this suggest?",opts:["New predictor significantly improves model fit and should be retained","New predictor adds minimal explanatory power not justifying added complexity — adjusted R-squared penalizes for the extra parameter","New predictor violates the multicollinearity assumption","Adjusted R-squared should always increase when a predictor is added"],ans:1,exp:"Unlike R-squared, adjusted R-squared penalizes for the number of predictors. It only increases if a new predictor improves fit by more than expected by chance. A decrease in adjusted R-squared (0.71 to 0.708) despite an increase in R-squared signals the new predictor adds noise rather than genuine signal."},
{id:102,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Diagnose non-linearity from residual plots",q:"A residual-vs-fitted plot for an MLR model shows a clear U-shaped pattern: negative residuals for low fitted values, positive for high fitted values, negative for intermediate values. What does this indicate?",opts:["Heteroscedasticity — the variance is non-constant","Non-linearity — the systematic component is incorrectly specified; a non-linear term such as a quadratic should be added","Non-independence of errors — observations are correlated","Multicollinearity between two predictors"],ans:1,exp:"A systematic U-shaped pattern in residuals indicates the mean function is misspecified — the relationship between predictors and target is not captured correctly by the current linear model. Adding quadratic terms, interactions, or using a GLM with log link would address the non-linear pattern. Heteroscedasticity produces a fan shape; multicollinearity does not produce patterns in residuals vs fitted."},
{id:103,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand impact of removing lower order terms",q:"An MLR model includes the quadratic term x-squared but not the linear term x. The hierarchical principle says this is problematic. What specific issue does it cause?",opts:["The model cannot be fitted because x-squared requires x to exist in the dataset","It forces the coefficient of x to be exactly zero, which is an assumption that should be tested not imposed by model specification","The quadratic term becomes identical to the linear term when x is not in the model","The R-squared value will be artificially inflated"],ans:1,exp:"Including x-squared without x forces the coefficient of x to be zero — essentially assuming x has no direct linear effect beyond its quadratic effect. This constraint should be tested rather than imposed by model structure. The hierarchical principle requires including all lower-order terms when higher-order terms are present."},
{id:104,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand the F-test vs t-tests",q:"An MLR model has all individual predictor t-test p-values above 0.15, but the F-test p-value is 0.003. How can this be?",opts:["This is mathematically impossible — if the F-test is significant, at least one t-test must be significant","Multicollinearity can cause individual t-tests to be insignificant even when predictors are collectively significant — the correlated predictors share credit making individual tests appear weak","The F-test is always more powerful than t-tests and the p-values are inconsistent","This means the null model is preferred over the fitted model"],ans:1,exp:"This is a classic consequence of multicollinearity. The F-test evaluates whether the predictors are collectively useful (testing all coefficients jointly) and can detect significance even when correlated predictors share credit and individually appear insignificant in t-tests. Multicollinearity inflates standard errors of individual coefficients making each t-test individually weak."},
{id:105,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply MLR to a practical scenario",q:"An MLR model for predicting insurance premium includes age, gender, and age times gender as predictors. The coefficient for age is 15, for gender (Male vs Female baseline) is -200, and for the interaction is 8. What is the predicted premium change per year of age for a male policyholder?",opts:["15 (only the age coefficient applies)","23 (age coefficient 15 plus interaction coefficient 8)","8 (only the interaction applies to males)","7 (15 minus 8)"],ans:1,exp:"For a male (Gender=1), the effective age slope is: age coefficient + interaction coefficient times Gender = 15 + 8 times 1 = 23. For each additional year of age, a male policyholder's predicted premium increases by 23. For a female (Gender=0), it would be 15 + 8 times 0 = 15 per year. The interaction captures the differential age effect by gender."},
{id:106,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand residuals in model evaluation",q:"In an MLR model, residuals are defined as:",opts:["The true error term epsilon in the population model","The estimated coefficients minus their true values","The difference between observed target values and model predictions for training observations","The difference between training RMSE and test RMSE"],ans:2,exp:"Residuals are the observed minus predicted values for training observations: e_i = y_i minus y-hat_i. They are estimates of the true but unobservable error terms epsilon_i. Residuals are used to diagnose violations of MLR assumptions through residual plots."},
{id:107,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify uses of the MLR model summary in R",q:"The lm() model summary output in R shows which of the following?",opts:["Only the predicted values for each training observation","Coefficient estimates with t-test results and the overall F-test result","Only the training RMSE and test RMSE","The optimal number of predictors selected by AIC"],ans:1,exp:"The model summary from lm() in R reveals: (1) the code used to create the model object, (2) coefficient estimates with their t-test results (estimate, standard error, t-statistic, p-value), and (3) the overall F-test result comparing the fitted model against the null model. It also shows R-squared and residual standard error."},
{id:108,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand conditions for valid inference",q:"An analyst finds severe heteroscedasticity in an MLR model. Why does this invalidate statistical inference even if coefficient estimates are still obtained?",opts:["Heteroscedasticity causes coefficient estimates to be biased — they no longer estimate the true population coefficients","Heteroscedasticity makes the OLS standard error estimates incorrect — t-tests and confidence intervals based on them are unreliable even though coefficient estimates remain unbiased","Heteroscedasticity means R-squared equals zero","Heteroscedasticity automatically increases the number of false positive significant predictors to exactly 50%"],ans:1,exp:"Under heteroscedasticity, OLS coefficient estimates remain unbiased (they still estimate true coefficients) but they are no longer the most efficient estimators. More importantly, the standard error estimates are incorrect, making t-test statistics, p-values, and confidence intervals unreliable. Hypothesis tests based on wrong standard errors lead to incorrect conclusions about predictor significance."},
{id:109,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare in-sample vs out-of-sample performance",q:"A model achieves R-squared=0.85 on training data but R-squared=0.32 on test data. What is the most likely explanation and appropriate remedy?",opts:["The test set is not representative of the population — collect more test data","The model is severely overfit — it has too many predictors or interactions relative to the training sample size; regularization, stepwise selection, or collecting more training data would help","The model needs a log transformation of the target variable","MLR cannot achieve high R-squared without standardizing all predictors first"],ans:1,exp:"A large gap between training R-squared (0.85) and test R-squared (0.32) is a clear sign of overfitting — the model memorized training data patterns including noise. With too many parameters relative to observations, MLR can fit training data perfectly but generalize poorly. Regularization (ridge, lasso) constrains coefficients; stepwise selection reduces the number of predictors; more training data helps dilute the noise."},
{id:110,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply MLR interpretation with continuous predictors",q:"An MLR predicting blood pressure: BP = 90 + 0.5 times Age + 3.2 times BMI - 5 times ExerciseHours. Which statement is true?",opts:["A person who exercises 1 more hour per week has blood pressure 5 points lower on average all else equal","Age is the most important predictor because it has the largest effect on blood pressure","BMI and ExerciseHours have identical magnitudes of effect on blood pressure","Each coefficient directly measures causal impact of its predictor on blood pressure"],ans:0,exp:"The coefficient -5 for ExerciseHours means each additional hour of weekly exercise is associated with a predicted 5-point decrease in blood pressure, holding age and BMI constant. This is a ceteris paribus interpretation. Coefficient magnitudes cannot be compared directly for importance unless predictors are standardized; correlation does not imply causation in MLR."},
{id:111,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand consequences of omitting relevant predictors",q:"An MLR model for insurance claims omits a relevant predictor (vehicle age) that is correlated with an included predictor (driver age). What is the consequence for the driver age coefficient estimate?",opts:["The driver age coefficient estimate is unaffected by omitting vehicle age","The driver age coefficient will be biased — it absorbs some of the effect of vehicle age in addition to its own true effect (omitted variable bias)","The model will automatically include vehicle age through the intercept term","The standard error of driver age coefficient will be artificially deflated"],ans:1,exp:"Omitted variable bias occurs when a relevant predictor correlated with included predictors is left out of the model. The included predictor (driver age) absorbs part of the omitted predictor's (vehicle age) effect. The estimated coefficient for driver age will be biased away from the true causal effect of driver age alone. This is a key limitation of observational MLR analysis."},
{id:112,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand model predictions vs individual outcomes",q:"An MLR model predicts hospital length of stay for a patient as 4.2 days. The patient actually stays 9 days. Which statement is most accurate?",opts:["The model is wrong and should be discarded","The prediction of 4.2 days represents the expected (mean) length of stay for patients with this profile; individual variation around this mean is captured by the random component","The model has made a 9-4.2=4.8 day error that reflects fundamental model failure","The residual of 4.8 days proves the model violates the normality assumption"],ans:1,exp:"MLR predictions represent the conditional mean of the target — the expected value for patients with the given predictor profile. Individual patients deviate from this mean due to the random component. A single patient staying 9 days vs. predicted 4.2 days is not evidence of model failure — it is expected variability. The residual of 4.8 is just one data point."},
{id:113,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret MLR coefficients for binary predictors",q:"An MLR model for loan approval probability includes IsRetiredFlag (1=retired, 0=working) with coefficient -0.08. The baseline is working. What does this mean?",opts:["Retired applicants have an 8% lower probability of approval on average compared to working applicants holding other predictors constant","Each retired applicant has exactly 0.08 less chance of approval","Retirement causes an 8% reduction in approval rates","The retirement effect is 8 times larger than any other predictor"],ans:0,exp:"A binary predictor coefficient in MLR represents the average difference in predicted target between the indicated level (retired) and baseline (working), holding other predictors constant. The -0.08 means retired applicants are predicted to have 0.08 (8 percentage points) lower approval probability on average than working applicants with the same other characteristics."},
{id:114,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand the intercept as a baseline",q:"In an MLR model: Premium = 200 + 50 times DriverAge + 30 times HasClaims - 20 times IsGoodDriver. What premium does the model predict for a driver with DriverAge=0, HasClaims=0, IsGoodDriver=0?",opts:["Zero — the model predicts zero premium when all predictors are zero","200 — the intercept gives the baseline predicted premium when all predictors equal zero","250 — the intercept plus the DriverAge coefficient","180 — 200 minus 20"],ans:1,exp:"The intercept is the predicted Y when all predictors equal zero. Here: 200 + 50(0) + 30(0) - 20(0) = 200. Whether this is physically meaningful (a driver with age=0?) is a separate question, but mathematically the intercept equals the prediction when all predictors are zero."},
{id:115,topic:"Multiple Linear Regression",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate the use of OLS for non-continuous targets",q:"An analyst applies OLS regression to predict a binary target (1=default, 0=no default). What are the fundamental problems with this approach?",opts:["OLS cannot compute residuals for binary targets","OLS predictions for binary targets can fall outside the range 0 to 1 making them uninterpretable as probabilities; and the homoscedasticity assumption is violated since variance of a binary variable depends on its mean","OLS will automatically convert the binary target to a continuous variable","Binary targets require at least 10000 observations for OLS to work correctly"],ans:1,exp:"Applying OLS to a binary target (Linear Probability Model) has two key problems: (1) predictions can be negative or exceed 1 — invalid as probabilities; (2) the variance of a Bernoulli variable is p(1-p) which varies with the mean, violating homoscedasticity. Logistic regression (GLM with binomial family and logit link) is the appropriate model for binary targets."},
{id:116,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define the purpose of regularization",q:"What is the primary purpose of regularization in statistical modeling?",opts:["To increase model flexibility by automatically adding interaction terms","To reduce variance at the expense of a slight increase in bias preventing overfitting","To convert all predictors to a common scale before modeling","To select the optimal test set size for model evaluation"],ans:1,exp:"The manual defines regularization as a technique that reduces the variance of a model at the expense of a slight increase in bias. By constraining coefficient estimates toward zero, regularization prevents overfitting especially when many predictors are present relative to observations."},
{id:117,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define AIC and BIC",q:"Which correctly describes the preference rule for AIC and BIC?",opts:["Higher AIC and BIC indicate a better model","Lower AIC and BIC indicate a better model","AIC should be minimized; BIC should be maximized","AIC and BIC only apply to regularization models not standard MLR"],ans:1,exp:"Both AIC and BIC balance model fit against complexity. Lower values are preferred — they indicate a model that fits well without unnecessary complexity. Both exhibit a U-shaped relationship with model flexibility, similar to test RMSE. They can be computed on the training set without needing a separate test set."},
{id:118,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Easy",lo:"Compare forward and backward selection",q:"Forward stepwise selection starts from the null model and adds predictors one at a time. When might forward selection be preferred over backward selection?",opts:["When the number of observations is smaller than the number of predictors (p > n) making the full model undefined","When the analyst wants more predictors in the final model","When all predictors are known to be relevant","When the F-test p-value is large"],ans:0,exp:"When p > n (more predictors than observations), the full model cannot be estimated by OLS — the system is underdetermined. Forward selection starts from the null model and can operate in high-dimensional settings where backward selection fails. The manual also notes that forward selection tends to result in fewer predictors overall."},
{id:119,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Compare ridge and lasso regression",q:"The key advantage of lasso over ridge regression is:",opts:["Lasso always produces lower test RMSE than ridge","Lasso can set some coefficients exactly to zero performing implicit variable selection","Lasso uses a simpler penalty function easier to compute","Lasso does not require standardization of predictors"],ans:1,exp:"Lasso (L1 penalty: lambda times sum of absolute values of coefficients) uses a constraint region with corners where coefficient estimates can be exactly zero — performing implicit variable selection. Ridge (L2 penalty: lambda times sum of squared coefficients) uses a circular constraint that only approaches zero asymptotically, retaining all predictors with shrunken coefficients."},
{id:120,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand elastic net",q:"Which statement about elastic net regression is correct?",opts:["Elastic net uses only the L1 penalty but applies it to a subset of predictors","Elastic net uses both L1 (lasso) and L2 (ridge) penalties combining their properties — it can perform variable selection while also handling correlated predictors better than pure lasso","Elastic net always produces the same result as ridge regression when tuning parameters are equal","Elastic net cannot handle factor variables"],ans:1,exp:"Elastic net adds both L1 and L2 penalty terms to the SSE objective. This hybrid approach inherits lasso's ability to set coefficients to zero (variable selection) and ridge's ability to handle groups of correlated predictors. The two tuning parameters (lambda for overall penalty, alpha for L1/L2 mix) are selected by cross-validation."},
{id:121,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret cross-validation plot for regularization",q:"A CV plot for lasso shows test MSE (U-shaped curve) vs log(lambda) on the x-axis. Two dashed lines are shown. The left dashed line corresponds to:",opts:["The lambda that produces the null model (all coefficients zero)","The lambda that minimizes cross-validation MSE (optimal regularization)","The lambda that maximizes the number of non-zero coefficients","The standard deviation of the cross-validation MSE estimates"],ans:1,exp:"The left dashed line marks lambda.min — the value of lambda that minimizes the cross-validation MSE. This is the optimal regularization strength in the sense of minimizing test error. The right dashed line marks lambda.1se — the largest lambda within one standard error of the minimum, representing a simpler but comparably performing model."},
{id:122,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain the 1-SE rule",q:"The 1-SE rule in regularization CV selects the largest lambda within one standard error of the minimum CV error. Why might this be preferred over selecting the minimum CV error lambda?",opts:["Because larger lambda values always produce better predictions","Because within the noise of CV any model within one SE of the minimum is statistically indistinguishable; the larger lambda gives a simpler model with comparable performance","Because the minimum CV error lambda violates the hierarchical principle","Because the 1-SE model always has higher R-squared"],ans:1,exp:"Cross-validation estimates have sampling variability. The minimum may be a statistical artifact rather than a true minimum. Any model within one SE of the minimum is indistinguishable from the best model given uncertainty. The 1-SE rule selects the simplest such model (largest lambda = most regularization = fewer non-zero coefficients), prioritizing parsimony without sacrificing meaningful accuracy."},
{id:123,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare BIC vs AIC penalization",q:"BIC tends to favor models with fewer predictors than AIC. What mathematical property causes this?",opts:["BIC uses a larger penalty term: log(n) times p vs AIC's 2 times p; for n greater than approximately 7.4 (always true in practice) log(n) is greater than 2","BIC maximizes training R-squared while AIC minimizes test error","BIC counts interactions separately while AIC does not","BIC is only computed for regularization models while AIC is for any model"],ans:0,exp:"AIC uses penalty 2p. BIC uses penalty log(n) times p. For any dataset with n > e-squared approximately 7.4 observations — always true in practice — log(n) > 2, making BIC's penalty stricter. This means BIC penalizes model complexity more heavily, resulting in preference for simpler models with fewer predictors."},
{id:124,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply backward selection principles",q:"During backward selection, which decision is made at each step?",opts:["The predictor with the largest absolute t-statistic is added","The predictor whose removal causes the largest decrease in AIC is removed","The predictor contributing least to fit relative to its complexity cost (smallest AIC increase on removal) is removed one at a time","All predictors with p-value greater than 0.10 are removed simultaneously"],ans:2,exp:"Backward selection starts with the full model and removes one term at a time. At each step, the term whose removal results in the model with the lowest AIC — i.e., the term contributing least to fit relative to complexity cost — is removed. The process continues until removing any remaining term would increase AIC, indicating no further improvement is possible."},
{id:125,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate lasso behavior as lambda increases",q:"In lasso regression, as lambda increases from 0 to infinity, what happens to the coefficient estimates?",opts:["They increase from their OLS values to infinity","They decrease from their OLS values toward zero eventually all reaching exactly zero (null model)","They alternate between positive and negative values","They remain at OLS values until a critical threshold then all jump to zero simultaneously"],ans:1,exp:"As lambda increases in lasso, the penalty on coefficient magnitude grows stronger, forcing coefficients progressively toward zero. At lambda=0, lasso gives OLS estimates. As lambda approaches infinity, all coefficients are forced to zero — the null model. Between these extremes, different predictors have their coefficients shrink to zero at different lambda values (lasso's variable selection property)."},
{id:126,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand binarization in stepwise selection",q:"Binarization in stepwise selection treats factor variables as binary (convert to numeric). What is a potential problem with this approach?",opts:["Binary variables cannot be used in MLR models","The factor levels are forced into a single linear sequence losing the flexibility of separate coefficients per level","Binarization increases the number of predictors beyond what MLR can handle","Binary variables require standardization before stepwise selection"],ans:1,exp:"Binarizing a factor forces it to be treated as a numeric variable in stepwise selection, assuming an ordinal linear relationship between levels. For example, binarizing region (Urban=1, Suburban=2, Rural=3) assumes a linear progression. This loses the ability to have separate effects per region and may incorrectly impose ordering."},
{id:127,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand ridge vs lasso for correlated predictors",q:"Two predictors X1 and X2 are highly correlated and both are genuinely predictive. How do ridge and lasso differ in handling this situation?",opts:["Ridge and lasso both retain one predictor and remove the other","Lasso tends to arbitrarily select one of the correlated predictors setting the other to zero; ridge distributes coefficient weight across both correlated predictors","Ridge always removes correlated predictors; lasso retains both","Neither method can handle correlated predictors — elastic net is required"],ans:1,exp:"With correlated predictors, lasso's L1 penalty tends to arbitrarily select one predictor while setting the other to zero — it has no mechanism to decide which to keep and may give inconsistent variable selection across different datasets. Ridge's L2 penalty distributes coefficient weight across both correlated predictors, shrinking both but keeping both. Elastic net was developed specifically to combine lasso's variable selection with ridge's handling of correlated groups."},
{id:128,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Easy",lo:"Apply AIC comparison",q:"AIC for two models: Model A (5 predictors) has AIC=284; Model B (8 predictors) has AIC=279. What conclusion follows?",opts:["Model A preferred because it has fewer predictors","Model B preferred because it has lower AIC — additional predictors add sufficient value to justify added complexity","Neither model is acceptable because both AIC values exceed 200","Model A preferred because AIC penalizes models with fewer predictors more heavily"],ans:1,exp:"AIC balances model fit and complexity — lower is better. Model B's AIC of 279 is lower than Model A's 284, meaning the improvement in fit from 3 additional predictors more than offsets the complexity penalty. AIC decreases when predictors genuinely add value and increases when added predictors are not justified."},
{id:129,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand cross-validation for lambda selection",q:"Why is cross-validation used to select the optimal lambda in regularization rather than training set performance?",opts:["Cross-validation is faster to compute than training set metrics for regularization","Training set performance always improves as lambda decreases (less regularization) regardless of overfitting — CV uses held-out data to find lambda with best true generalization","Cross-validation accounts for the normality assumption required by ridge regression","Lambda selection does not require any optimization for lasso"],ans:1,exp:"As lambda decreases toward zero in lasso or ridge, coefficients approach OLS estimates and training SSE monotonically decreases — training error always favors less regularization regardless of overfitting. Cross-validation uses held-out folds to evaluate test-like performance, finding the lambda that optimizes generalization rather than training fit. This prevents selecting the null lambda (no regularization) every time."},
{id:130,topic:"Regularization",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare elastic net tuning parameters",q:"Elastic net has two tuning parameters: lambda and alpha. What does the alpha parameter control?",opts:["The number of iterations in the cross-validation procedure","The mix between L1 (lasso) and L2 (ridge) penalties: alpha=0 is pure ridge, alpha=1 is pure lasso","The size of the test set used for cross-validation","The standardization of predictors before regularization"],ans:1,exp:"In elastic net: penalty = alpha times lasso penalty + (1-alpha) times ridge penalty. Alpha controls the balance: alpha=0 gives pure ridge regression, alpha=1 gives pure lasso, and values in between give a mixture. Lambda controls the overall strength of regularization. Both parameters are typically selected via cross-validation."},
{id:131,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Explain how GLM extends MLR",q:"What is the primary way GLM extends MLR?",opts:["GLM can include more predictors than MLR","GLM allows the target variable to follow distributions from the linear exponential family beyond just the normal distribution","GLM uses a different optimization method that is faster than OLS","GLM does not require a training set for parameter estimation"],ans:1,exp:"The most important extension of GLM over MLR is relaxing the normal distribution assumption. MLR requires the target to be normally distributed. GLM allows any distribution from the linear exponential family including Poisson, Gamma, Binomial, and Inverse Gaussian. A link function connects the mean of the chosen distribution to the linear predictor."},
{id:132,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify distributions in the linear exponential family",q:"Which distribution is NOT in the linear exponential family as covered in Exam PA?",opts:["Normal (Gaussian)","Poisson","Uniform distribution","Gamma"],ans:2,exp:"The uniform distribution is not in the linear exponential family. The five main distributions for Exam PA are: Normal (Gaussian), Binomial, Poisson, Gamma, and Inverse Gaussian. The negative binomial and Tweedie are also covered as additional distributions."},
{id:133,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Match GLM distribution to target type",q:"Which GLM distribution is most appropriate for modeling a binary (0/1) target variable?",opts:["Gamma — for continuous positive targets","Poisson — for count targets","Binomial (Bernoulli) — for binary targets","Inverse Gaussian — for positive continuous targets"],ans:2,exp:"Binary (0/1) targets follow a Bernoulli distribution, a special case of Binomial with one trial. The Binomial family with logit link (logistic regression) is the standard GLM for binary classification. Poisson is for counts; Gamma and Inverse Gaussian are for continuous positive responses."},
{id:134,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify the role of the link function",q:"In a GLM, the link function g() satisfies which relationship?",opts:["g(mu) = Y","g(mu) = X times beta (the linear predictor)","g(mu) = epsilon (the error term)","g(mu) = sigma-squared (the variance)"],ans:1,exp:"The link function connects the mean of the target distribution (mu) to the linear predictor (X times beta). The relationship is: g(mu) = beta-0 + beta-1 times X1 + ... + beta-p times Xp. Applying the inverse link function gives predictions back on the original scale: mu = g-inverse(X times beta)."},
{id:135,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain the canonical link function",q:"What is the canonical link for the Poisson distribution and why is it recommended?",opts:["Identity link — because Poisson counts are additive on the natural scale","Log link — because it guarantees positive predictions and is the canonical link simplifying the log-likelihood","Logit link — because Poisson probabilities must be between 0 and 1","Inverse link — because it handles the reciprocal relationship in count data"],ans:1,exp:"The log link is recommended for Poisson regression for two reasons: (1) it guarantees positive predictions since exp of any real number is positive, consistent with count data that cannot be negative; (2) it is the canonical link for Poisson distribution which simplifies the log-likelihood. The manual states there is generally no reason to choose a different link function for Poisson regression."},
{id:136,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret logistic regression coefficients",q:"A logistic regression model (logit link) has coefficient 0.04 for age. Which interpretation is correct?",opts:["Each additional year of age increases predicted probability of the outcome by 0.04","Each additional year of age increases the log-odds of the outcome by 0.04","Each additional year of age multiplies the probability by 0.04","Age has a 4% effect on the outcome probability"],ans:1,exp:"With a logit link, coefficients represent changes in the log-odds (logit) of the outcome per unit increase in the predictor. A coefficient of 0.04 means each additional year of age increases the log-odds by 0.04. The multiplicative change in odds is exp(0.04) approximately 1.041. The effect on probability is not constant — it depends on the current probability level."},
{id:137,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand odds and the logit link",q:"If the predicted probability of an event is 0.25, what are the odds?",opts:["0.25","0.33","0.75","3.0"],ans:1,exp:"Odds = p divided by (1-p) = 0.25 divided by (1-0.25) = 0.25 divided by 0.75 = 1/3 approximately 0.333. Odds represent how many times more likely the event is to occur than not. Probability 0.25 means a 1-in-4 chance, so the event is 3 times less likely than not occurring — odds of 1 to 3 or 0.333."},
{id:138,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Use the confusion matrix",q:"A confusion matrix shows: True Positives=80, False Positives=20, False Negatives=30, True Negatives=870. What is the sensitivity?",opts:["0.800","0.727","0.967","0.889"],ans:1,exp:"Sensitivity = TP divided by (TP plus FN) = 80 divided by (80 plus 30) = 80 divided by 110 approximately 0.727. Sensitivity measures the proportion of actual positives correctly identified. Of 110 true positives, the model correctly identifies 80 (72.7%). This is also called the true positive rate or recall."},
{id:139,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand the AUC metric",q:"A logistic regression model has AUC=0.50. What does this indicate?",opts:["The model predicts the outcome correctly 50% of the time","The model performs no better than random chance — it has no discriminatory ability","The model has 50% sensitivity and 50% specificity","The model is overfit"],ans:1,exp:"AUC (area under the ROC curve) measures the model's ability to discriminate between positive and negative classes. AUC=0.5 is equivalent to random classification — no better than a coin flip. AUC=1.0 is perfect discrimination. AUC is not the same as accuracy; it measures the ranking quality of predicted probabilities."},
{id:140,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Adjust the classification cutoff",q:"A logistic model predicts hospital readmission. The hospital wants to identify as many at-risk patients as possible (maximize sensitivity) even if some healthy patients are also flagged. What change to the cutoff achieves this?",opts:["Increase the cutoff (e.g., from 0.5 to 0.8) — higher threshold flags fewer patients","Lower the cutoff (e.g., from 0.5 to 0.2) — more patients will be predicted positive increasing sensitivity","Remove all patients with predicted probability exactly 0.5","Use AUC instead of accuracy for threshold selection"],ans:1,exp:"Sensitivity = TP divided by (TP plus FN). To increase sensitivity, more patients need to be predicted positive (reducing false negatives). Lowering the cutoff from 0.5 to 0.2 means a patient needs only 20% predicted probability to be flagged — more patients will be flagged, catching more true positives at the cost of more false positives (lower specificity)."},
{id:141,topic:"GLM",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand overdispersion in GLMs",q:"A Poisson GLM is fitted to claim count data. The ratio of residual deviance to residual degrees of freedom is 4.8. What does this indicate and how should it be addressed?",opts:["The model is a perfect fit — ratios near 5 are ideal","Overdispersion is present (ratio >> 1); variance exceeds the Poisson mean assumption. A negative binomial GLM or quasi-Poisson should be considered","Underdispersion — too little variance in the data","The link function is wrong and should be changed from log to identity"],ans:1,exp:"For a well-fitted Poisson model, residual deviance divided by degrees of freedom should be approximately 1 (Poisson assumes mean = variance). A ratio of 4.8 indicates severe overdispersion — actual variance is approximately 4.8 times the Poisson-assumed variance. This leads to underestimated standard errors. Solutions: negative binomial distribution or quasi-Poisson with estimated dispersion parameter."},
{id:142,topic:"GLM",diff:"Hard",lo:"Interpret exposure in Poisson regression",q:"A Poisson regression includes log(PolicyYears) as an offset. What is the effect of this offset on the model?",opts:["It increases the regularization penalty proportionally to policy years","It allows the model to predict the rate of claims per policy year rather than total count accounting for different exposure periods","It converts the count target to a continuous probability","It removes the need for a log link function"],ans:1,exp:"An offset in Poisson regression is a known quantity added to the linear predictor with coefficient forced to 1. log(PolicyYears) as offset means: log(mu) = log(PolicyYears) + X times beta, which is equivalent to log(mu divided by PolicyYears) = X times beta. The model predicts claims per policy year, properly accounting for different exposure periods."},
{id:143,topic:"GLM",diff:"Hard",lo:"Select between competing GLM distributions",q:"A target variable represents total medical costs per patient: always positive, right-skewed, with variance appearing to increase with the mean. Which distribution is most appropriate?",opts:["Normal (Gaussian) with identity link — because costs are measured on a natural scale","Poisson with log link — because costs are a form of count","Gamma with log link — because Gamma is appropriate for positive right-skewed continuous data with variance proportional to mean squared","Binomial with logit link — because costs can be high or low"],ans:2,exp:"The Gamma distribution models continuous positive responses with right skew. Its variance function is Var(mu) = phi times mu-squared (variance proportional to mean squared), which matches the observed pattern where high-cost patients have more variable costs. The log link ensures positive predictions. This is the standard GLM choice for insurance claim severities and medical costs."},
{id:144,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand the ROC curve",q:"The ROC curve plots sensitivity (true positive rate) vs 1-specificity (false positive rate) for all possible cutoff values. Which point on the ROC curve represents the optimal cutoff when sensitivity and specificity are equally valued?",opts:["The point closest to the bottom-right corner","The point closest to the top-left corner (0,1) — highest sensitivity with lowest false positive rate","The point at coordinates (0.5, 0.5) representing random classification","The point where the curve crosses the diagonal line"],ans:1,exp:"The ROC curve goes from (0,0) at maximum cutoff to (1,1) at minimum cutoff. The top-left corner (0,1) represents perfect discrimination (100% sensitivity, 100% specificity). The optimal operating point when both metrics are equally valued is the one closest to (0,1). Points on the diagonal represent random classification."},
{id:145,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply GLM to count targets",q:"A Poisson regression model predicts workplace accidents per year. The linear predictor for a specific company is -0.5. What is the predicted number of accidents?",opts:["-0.5","0.5","0.607","1.649"],ans:2,exp:"For Poisson regression with log link: mu = exp(linear predictor) = exp(-0.5) approximately 0.607. The log link ensures positive predictions even when the linear predictor is negative. A predicted rate of 0.607 means approximately 0.6 expected accidents per year for this company."},
{id:146,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify appropriate GLM for continuous positive target",q:"Annual insurance premium is always positive and right-skewed. Which GLM setup is most appropriate?",opts:["Normal distribution with identity link","Binomial distribution with logit link","Gamma distribution with log link","Poisson distribution with log link"],ans:2,exp:"Gamma distribution with log link is appropriate for continuous positive right-skewed targets like insurance premiums. The Gamma distribution has positive support, models right-skewed data, and has variance proportional to mean squared which is typical for monetary amounts. The log link ensures positive predictions."},
{id:147,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand GLM parameter estimation",q:"Unlike MLR which uses OLS, GLMs use what estimation method?",opts:["Ordinary least squares with modified penalty term","Maximum likelihood estimation via iterative numerical algorithms","Bayesian posterior mean estimation","Gradient descent applied to residual sum of squares"],ans:1,exp:"GLM parameters are estimated using maximum likelihood estimation (MLE). Because closed-form solutions are generally not available (unlike OLS for MLR), iterative numerical algorithms such as iteratively reweighted least squares (IRLS) are used. MLE finds parameter values that maximize the probability of observing the actual data under the assumed distribution."},
{id:148,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret deviance in GLM",q:"Deviance in a GLM is defined as -2 times (log-likelihood of fitted model minus log-likelihood of saturated model). A lower deviance indicates:",opts:["A more complex model with more parameters","A better-fitting model closer to the saturated (perfect fit) model","A model with less regularization","A more interpretable model"],ans:1,exp:"Deviance measures how far the fitted model is from the saturated model (a perfect fit with one parameter per observation). Lower deviance means the fitted model explains data nearly as well as a perfect fit. Deviance plays the same role in GLMs that SSE plays in MLR."},
{id:149,topic:"GLM",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply likelihood ratio test for model comparison",q:"Two nested GLMs: Model A (8 predictors, deviance=145) and Model B (5 predictors, deviance=152). Deviance difference is 7; chi-squared critical value at 3 degrees of freedom is 7.81. What conclusion follows?",opts:["Model A is significantly better — it has lower deviance","Adding 3 extra predictors does not significantly improve fit (deviance difference 7 < critical value 7.81); Model B is preferred for parsimony","Model B is better because it has fewer predictors","Test cannot be conducted because models have different numbers of predictors"],ans:1,exp:"The likelihood ratio test uses deviance differences which follow a chi-squared distribution with df = difference in parameters. Delta deviance=7, df=8-5=3, critical value=7.81. Since 7 < 7.81 we fail to reject the null (that 3 extra predictors have zero coefficients). The 3 extra predictors do not significantly improve fit — Model B is preferred for parsimony."},
{id:150,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand logistic regression classification",q:"A logistic regression outputs predicted probability=0.73. Using a cutoff of 0.5, what is the classification?",opts:["Negative (class 0) because 0.73 is less than 1","Positive (class 1) because 0.73 exceeds the 0.5 cutoff","Negative because model is uncertain when probability is not near 0 or 1","No classification can be made until AUC is computed"],ans:1,exp:"When predicted probability exceeds the cutoff, the observation is classified as positive (class 1). With cutoff=0.5 and predicted probability=0.73 > 0.5, the customer is classified as positive. The choice of cutoff depends on the relative costs of false positives and false negatives in the business context."},
{id:151,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand AIC for GLM model selection",q:"An analyst uses AIC to compare two non-nested GLMs: Model A (Gamma distribution, log link, AIC=1205) and Model B (Inverse Gaussian distribution, log link, AIC=1198). Which model should be preferred?",opts:["Model A because Gamma is more commonly used in insurance","Model B because lower AIC indicates better balance of fit and complexity","Neither — AIC can only compare nested models","Model A because Gamma is more robust to distributional misspecification"],ans:1,exp:"AIC can compare any models fitted to the same dataset whether nested or not. Lower AIC is preferred. Model B's AIC of 1198 is lower than Model A's 1205 indicating Model B (Inverse Gaussian) provides better fit relative to its complexity. Note that likelihood ratio tests using deviance differences are only valid for nested models; AIC comparison is valid for non-nested models."},
{id:152,topic:"GLM",diff:"Hard",lo:"Interpret GLM output with interaction",q:"A logistic regression (logit link) output: Intercept=-2.1, Age=0.03, IsMale=0.4, IsMale:Age=0.01. For a 40-year-old male, what is the predicted log-odds?",opts:["-2.1 + 0.03(40) + 0.4(1) + 0.01(1)(40) = -0.1","0.03 times 40 times 0.4 times 0.01 = 0.0005","-2.1 + 0.03(40) = -0.9","0.4 + 0.01(40) = 0.8"],ans:0,exp:"For a 40-year-old male (IsMale=1, Age=40): Log-odds = -2.1 + 0.03(40) + 0.4(1) + 0.01(1)(40) = -2.1 + 1.2 + 0.4 + 0.4 = -0.1. The interaction 0.01 means for males each additional year of age adds 0.03+0.01=0.04 to log-odds vs 0.03 for females. Predicted probability = exp(-0.1)/(1+exp(-0.1)) approximately 0.475."},
{id:153,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand negative binomial for overdispersed count data",q:"A Poisson GLM for claim counts shows the sample variance (340) is much larger than the sample mean (12). What does this indicate and what alternative is appropriate?",opts:["Underdispersion — Gamma distribution should be used","Overdispersion — the negative binomial distribution which assumes variance > mean is more appropriate","Perfect fit — variance should equal mean in all GLMs","The log link function should be changed to identity link"],ans:1,exp:"Poisson regression assumes mean equals variance (equidispersion). When variance (340) substantially exceeds mean (12), there is overdispersion — Poisson model fit is poor and standard errors are underestimated. The negative binomial distribution explicitly models variance > mean, making it the natural alternative for overdispersed count data."},
{id:154,topic:"GLM",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand logit vs probit links",q:"Both logit and probit links are valid for binary targets. Which statement correctly distinguishes them for practical use?",opts:["Logit produces probabilities between 0 and 1; probit does not","Logit coefficients can be interpreted via log-odds (exp(coef) = odds ratio) which is articulable; probit interpretation is harder to explain beyond directional impact","Probit always achieves higher AUC than logit","Logit requires normally distributed predictors; probit does not"],ans:1,exp:"Both logit and probit links produce valid probability predictions. The practical difference is interpretability: logit coefficients can be interpreted as changes in log-odds and exp(coef) gives the odds ratio — a concept that can be explained to non-statisticians. Probit coefficients relate to the normal distribution CDF and are harder to interpret. The manual recommends logit for this reason."},
{id:155,topic:"GLM",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand GLM assumptions",q:"Which of the following is a key assumption of GLMs that is NOT required by standard MLR?",opts:["The errors are normally distributed","The target variable follows a distribution from the linear exponential family","The predictors are measured without error","The residuals have zero mean"],ans:1,exp:"GLMs require the target distribution to belong to the linear exponential family (Normal, Binomial, Poisson, Gamma, Inverse Gaussian). Standard MLR is a special case where the target is assumed Normal — which is within this family. The additional flexibility of GLMs comes from allowing non-Normal distributions for counts, proportions, and skewed positive data."},
{id:156,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define components of a decision tree",q:"In a decision tree, the topmost node that contains all training observations is called the:",opts:["Terminal node","Leaf node","Root node","Parent node"],ans:2,exp:"The root node is the starting node at the top of the tree. It contains all training observations and is where the first split is made. Terminal nodes (leaves) are at the bottom making predictions. Parent and child nodes describe relative relationships within the tree structure."},
{id:157,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Easy",lo:"Make predictions from a regression tree",q:"A regression tree terminal node contains training observations with target values 4, 6, 8, 10, 12. What prediction does the tree make for any new observation falling into this node?",opts:["6 (the median)","8 (the mean)","4 (the minimum)","12 (the maximum)"],ans:1,exp:"Regression trees predict the mean of training target values in the terminal node. Mean = (4+6+8+10+12)/5 = 40/5 = 8. All observations assigned to this terminal node receive the same prediction of 8."},
{id:158,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Easy",lo:"Make predictions from a classification tree",q:"A classification tree terminal node contains 15 observations: 9 Fraud and 6 Legitimate. What prediction does the tree assign to observations in this node?",opts:["Legitimate because it is safer to not flag fraud","Fraud because it is the majority class","No prediction because neither class has more than 50%","The probability 9/15 = 0.60"],ans:1,exp:"Classification trees predict the majority class of training observations in each terminal node. With 9 Fraud vs 6 Legitimate, Fraud is the majority class — all observations assigned to this node are predicted as Fraud. Note that 0.60 is also a valid probability output but the class prediction is the majority class."},
{id:159,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define tree flexibility via terminal nodes",q:"How is the flexibility of a decision tree measured?",opts:["By the depth of the deepest terminal node","By the number of predictors used in splits","By the number of terminal nodes — more terminal nodes means more flexibility","By the number of training observations per terminal node"],ans:2,exp:"The number of terminal nodes measures flexibility in decision trees. More terminal nodes = more regions in the predictor space = more complex flexible model with higher variance and lower bias. A tree with 1 terminal node predicts the overall mean (null model). A tree with one node per observation is fully flexible but completely overfit."},
{id:160,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply recursive binary splitting criterion",q:"At a node, two candidate splits are considered: Split A gives total SSE of 130 across child nodes; Split B gives total SSE of 100. Which split is selected?",opts:["Split A because it produces a more balanced partition","Split B because it produces a lower total SSE of 100","Either — the algorithm randomly selects between ties","Split A because higher SSE indicates more variability to model"],ans:1,exp:"Recursive binary splitting selects the split that minimizes total SSE across the two resulting child nodes. Split B total SSE=100 is lower than Split A total SSE=130. The balance of the partition is not considered — only total SSE reduction matters."},
{id:161,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand the Gini index splitting criterion",q:"A classification tree node has 60 successes and 40 failures out of 100 observations. What is the Gini index for this node?",opts:["0.24","0.48","0.50","0.60"],ans:1,exp:"Gini index = 1 minus (p-0 squared + p-1 squared) where p-0=0.40 and p-1=0.60. Gini = 1 minus (0.40 squared + 0.60 squared) = 1 minus (0.16 + 0.36) = 1 minus 0.52 = 0.48. A purely mixed node (50/50) has maximum Gini=0.50; a pure node (all one class) has Gini=0. Lower Gini = purer node."},
{id:162,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain cost-complexity pruning",q:"The complexity parameter (cp) in cost-complexity pruning controls the size of the final tree. If cp is set to a very large value, what effect does this have?",opts:["The tree grows very large with many terminal nodes","The tree is aggressively pruned to a very small size — only splits with very large SSE reductions are kept","The tree uses entropy instead of Gini as its splitting criterion","The tree ignores training data and produces the null model"],ans:1,exp:"A larger cp requires a larger improvement in fit to justify each additional split. With a very large cp, only splits producing enormous SSE reductions are kept — resulting in a very small heavily pruned tree. A cp of 1 would produce the null model. Selecting cp via cross-validation balances the bias-variance tradeoff."},
{id:163,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret a decision tree prediction",q:"A decision tree has splits: root node splits on Age < 30 (left if yes). Left node splits on Gender=Male (leaf predicts 2.1) or Female (leaf predicts 1.5). Right node (Age >= 30) predicts 0.8. A 25-year-old female is predicted to have value:",opts:["0.8","2.1","1.5","1.2"],ans:2,exp:"Trace the observation: Age=25 < 30 therefore go left. Gender=Female therefore leaf predicting 1.5. The prediction is 1.5. Decision trees apply if-then rules directing each observation to a specific terminal node where the prediction is assigned."},
{id:164,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare Gini index and entropy as splitting criteria",q:"Both Gini index and entropy are used as impurity measures for classification trees. Which statement best distinguishes them?",opts:["Gini is used for regression trees; entropy is used for classification trees","Entropy tends to produce slightly different split choices than Gini due to different mathematical properties but resulting trees are usually very similar in practice; Gini is computationally faster","Gini always selects splits giving lower misclassification error than entropy","Entropy is only valid for binary targets; Gini works for multi-class"],ans:1,exp:"Both Gini index and entropy measure node impurity and serve as splitting criteria. Their mathematical forms differ (Gini uses squared proportions; entropy uses log proportions), leading to slightly different assessments. In practice they usually produce very similar trees. Gini is slightly faster to compute since it avoids the log calculation. Neither is universally superior."},
{id:165,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand surrogate splits for missing data",q:"A decision tree is trained with surrogate splits enabled. At prediction time an observation has a missing value for the root node split variable. How does the tree handle this?",opts:["The observation is excluded from prediction","The missing value is imputed with training set mean before splitting","A surrogate split — an alternative splitting rule using a different predictor that closely mimics the original split — is used to direct the observation to the appropriate child node","The observation is always sent to the larger child node"],ans:2,exp:"Surrogate splits are backup splitting rules stored for each node. They use alternative predictors that most closely replicate the behavior of the chosen split variable when it is missing. If the root node split on X1 is unavailable due to X1 missing, the best surrogate (the predictor whose split most agrees with X1's split) is used instead."},
{id:166,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Hard",lo:"Assess when decision trees are preferred over GLMs",q:"A dataset has 10 variables where the sum of all variables equals 100% (percentages of time spent in different activities). A GLM cannot be fitted with all 10. What advantage does a decision tree have?",opts:["Decision trees can be fitted with any number of predictors regardless of perfect multicollinearity","Decision trees are immune to the perfect multicollinearity caused by the sum constraint — they select only the most useful splitting variables and are not affected by the linear dependence","Decision trees automatically transform variables to break multicollinearity","Decision trees require fewer observations than GLMs"],ans:1,exp:"When variables sum to a constant, perfect multicollinearity is present — one variable is a linear combination of the others. GLM's OLS-based estimation cannot handle this. Decision trees are unaffected because they select splitting variables greedily one at a time without requiring matrix inversion. The manual uses this exact example from the Mining Data (PCT_HRS variables summing to 100%)."},
{id:167,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand the greedy nature of recursive binary splitting",q:"Recursive binary splitting is described as a greedy algorithm. What does this mean in the context of decision tree construction?",opts:["The algorithm selects the most complex possible split at each node to maximize flexibility","The algorithm selects the best split at each node without considering how future splits will be affected — it optimizes locally at each step","The algorithm greedily retains all predictors requiring explicit pruning to remove them","The algorithm selects splits based on final test RMSE rather than training SSE"],ans:1,exp:"A greedy algorithm makes the locally optimal choice at each step without considering global consequences. For decision trees this means selecting the single best split at each node based on current SSE reduction, without considering whether a slightly worse split now might enable much better splits downstream. This can miss the globally optimal tree but is computationally tractable."},
{id:168,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand tree depth",q:"A decision tree has root at depth 0. A split creates two child nodes at depth 1 which each split creating grandchild nodes at depth 2. What is the tree depth?",opts:["0","1","2","4 (total number of nodes)"],ans:2,exp:"Tree depth is defined as the number of edges along the longest path from the root node to a leaf. Root is at depth 0, its children at depth 1, their children at depth 2. The depth of the tree is the maximum depth of any leaf — in this case 2."},
{id:169,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply cross-validation to select optimal tree size",q:"Cross-validation selects optimal cp for a decision tree. CV error is lowest at cp=0.01 and increases for both smaller and larger cp values. What does cp=0.01 represent?",opts:["The smallest tree with 1 terminal node","The tree that best balances bias and variance for generalization to new data","The tree with the lowest training error regardless of complexity","The cp value at which all splits are removed"],ans:1,exp:"Cross-validation identifies the cp value that minimizes test error — the bias-variance optimal point. At cp=0.01 the tree is complex enough to capture true patterns (low bias) but not so complex that it memorizes training noise (acceptable variance). This is exactly the U-shape test RMSE pattern applied to tree size."},
{id:170,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate decision tree advantages and disadvantages",q:"Which combination of properties is MOST accurate regarding decision trees compared to GLMs?",opts:["Decision trees are always more accurate and easier to interpret than GLMs","Decision trees require fewer distributional assumptions and handle interactions automatically but are unstable (small data changes can produce very different trees) and generally less accurate than ensemble methods","Decision trees are more accurate than GLMs but require more assumptions about the target distribution","Decision trees and GLMs have identical accuracy when training set size exceeds 1000 observations"],ans:1,exp:"Decision trees advantages: no distributional assumptions, handle non-linear relationships and interactions automatically, immune to multicollinearity, naturally interpretable. Disadvantages: high variance/instability (small training changes produce very different trees), generally lower accuracy than ensemble methods, greedy algorithm may miss optimal splits. GLMs are more stable but require distributional and linearity assumptions."},
{id:171,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply tree splitting to categorical predictors",q:"A categorical predictor Season has 4 levels. How many possible binary partitions exist for this variable in a decision tree split?",opts:["4","7","8","15"],ans:1,exp:"For a factor with L levels, the number of possible binary partitions is 2 to the power (L-1) minus 1. With L=4: 2 to the power 3 minus 1 = 8 minus 1 = 7. Possible groupings include: {Spring} vs {Summer, Fall, Winter}; {Summer} vs {Spring, Fall, Winter}; {Spring, Summer} vs {Fall, Winter}; and so on."},
{id:172,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand Poisson regression trees",q:"When would a Poisson regression tree be more appropriate than a standard regression tree for a count target?",opts:["When the target has more zeros than non-zeros","When the target is a count variable with non-negative integer values and properties suggesting Poisson distribution","When the number of predictors exceeds the number of observations","When the target has been log-transformed"],ans:1,exp:"A Poisson regression tree uses Poisson deviance as the splitting criterion instead of SSE. It is more appropriate for count data (non-negative integers) where the Poisson distribution's properties are relevant. Standard regression trees use SSE and predict node means which can produce non-integer predictions. Poisson trees make predictions respecting the count nature of the target."},
{id:173,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret the complexity parameter table",q:"In R's rpart output, the complexity parameter (cp) table shows cp values, number of splits, and cross-validation error for each tree size. How is this table used to select the optimal tree?",opts:["Select the tree with the most splits — more complex trees always have lower CV error","Select the smallest cp — it corresponds to the most complex tree","Select the tree with lowest cross-validation error or apply 1-SE rule to choose a simpler model with comparable CV error","Select the tree with cp closest to 0.01 as this is always optimal"],ans:2,exp:"The cp table from rpart shows cross-validation error (xerror) for each level of tree complexity. The standard approach is to select the cp corresponding to minimum xerror (lowest CV error). The 1-SE rule selects the largest cp (simplest tree) whose xerror is within one standard deviation (xstd) of the minimum — providing a more parsimonious model that performs comparably. The cp=0.01 default is a starting point not always optimal."},
{id:174,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand decision tree predictions for all observations in a node",q:"In a regression tree, a terminal node contains 25 training observations with target values ranging from 8 to 42, with mean=18. A new observation is routed to this node. What is its prediction?",opts:["The median of the 25 values in the node","18 (the mean of the 25 training target values in the node)","The minimum value 8 (most conservative prediction)","The value of the new observation's most similar training neighbor"],ans:1,exp:"In a regression tree, every observation assigned to a terminal node receives the same prediction: the mean of the target values for all training observations in that node. Here the prediction is 18 regardless of which specific observation falls into this node or how close its predictors are to any individual training observation."},
{id:175,topic:"Decision Trees",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply information gain calculation",q:"A classification tree node has 100 observations with 70 positives and 30 negatives. A proposed split creates a left node (40 obs, 35 positive) and right node (60 obs, 35 positive). What happens to the Gini index after this split?",opts:["Gini increases because we created two impure nodes","Gini decreases because each child node is purer than the parent node on average","Gini remains exactly the same because the total number of positives and negatives is unchanged","Gini cannot be computed until we know the predictor used for splitting"],ans:1,exp:"Parent Gini: 1-(0.7^2+0.3^2) = 1-0.58 = 0.42. Left node (35/40 positive, 5/40 negative): Gini = 1-(0.875^2+0.125^2) = 1-0.781 = 0.219. Right node (35/60 positive, 25/60 negative): Gini = 1-(0.583^2+0.417^2) = 1-0.514 = 0.486. Weighted Gini after split: (40/100)(0.219)+(60/100)(0.486) = 0.088+0.292 = 0.380. Since 0.380 < 0.42, the split reduces Gini (improves purity)."},
{id:176,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define bootstrap sampling",q:"Bootstrap sampling creates each sample by drawing from the training set with replacement. What percentage of unique observations does each bootstrap sample typically contain?",opts:["100% — exactly the same observations as the original","50% — half the observations are randomly selected","Approximately 63.2% — the remaining 36.8% are out-of-bag observations","Exactly 70% — the standard train/test split"],ans:2,exp:"When sampling n observations with replacement from a dataset of n, the probability that any specific observation is NOT selected is (1-1/n)^n which approaches 1/e approximately 0.368 as n increases. Therefore approximately 36.8% are not selected (OOB) and approximately 63.2% are included."},
{id:177,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Easy",lo:"Describe the random forest prediction process",q:"For a random forest regression model, how are predictions from individual trees combined into a final prediction?",opts:["Prediction from the tree with lowest training error is used","Predictions are averaged across all trees in the forest","Majority vote of tree predictions is used","Median prediction across all trees is used"],ans:1,exp:"For random forest regression, predictions are averaged: the final prediction is the mean of all individual tree predictions. For classification, the most frequent class prediction (majority vote) across all trees is used. Averaging reduces variance compared to a single tree — this is the fundamental mechanism of random forest improvement."},
{id:178,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define out-of-bag observations",q:"In a random forest, what are out-of-bag (OOB) observations?",opts:["Observations collected outside the normal data collection period","Observations in the test set reserved for final evaluation","Training observations not included in a specific bootstrap sample — can be used to estimate that tree's prediction error","Observations identified as outliers and excluded from model training"],ans:2,exp:"Each bootstrap sample includes approximately 63.2% of unique training observations. The remaining approximately 36.8% — not used to fit that particular tree — are the OOB observations. Predictions for each observation from all trees where it was OOB can be aggregated to produce an OOB error estimate — a free internal estimate of test performance."},
{id:179,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain random feature selection in random forests",q:"Why does random forest use a random subset of features at each split rather than considering all features?",opts:["To speed up computation by reducing the number of splits evaluated","To prevent all trees from being dominated by the same strong predictors reducing correlation between trees and improving variance reduction","To enable random forests to handle missing values more effectively","To ensure the forest always achieves higher accuracy than a single decision tree"],ans:1,exp:"If all features were considered at every split (bagging), all trees would likely make the same top splits using dominant predictors. Highly correlated trees do not reduce variance much when averaged. By restricting to a random subset (sqrt(p) for classification, p/3 for regression), trees are forced to use different predictors, becoming less correlated. Averaging uncorrelated trees reduces variance more effectively."},
{id:180,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Distinguish random forests from boosting",q:"Which statement correctly describes the fundamental difference between random forests and boosting in their approach to building trees?",opts:["Random forests use classification trees; boosting uses regression trees","Random forests build trees independently in parallel reducing variance; boosting builds trees sequentially where each corrects previous errors reducing bias","Both build trees sequentially but random forests use different training subsets","Random forests limit tree depth; boosting allows unlimited depth"],ans:1,exp:"The key distinction: Random forests build many independent trees on bootstrap samples then average — reducing variance. Boosting builds trees sequentially: each new tree is fitted to the residuals (errors) of all previous trees combined, specifically targeting what the current ensemble gets wrong — sequential bias reduction is boosting's defining mechanism."},
{id:181,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret variable importance in random forests",q:"In a random forest variable importance table, Mean Decrease in MSE is 45.2 for predictor X1 and 2.1 for predictor X2. What does this indicate?",opts:["X1 has much larger coefficient values than X2 in the linear model","X1 contributes much more to prediction accuracy — permuting X1 values causes a much larger increase in out-of-bag MSE than permuting X2","X2 should be removed from the model because its importance is below 5","Both variables should be kept since the model already selected them"],ans:1,exp:"Mean Decrease in MSE permutes each predictor's values on OOB observations and measures how much MSE increases. A large value (X1=45.2) means permuting X1 greatly disrupts predictions — X1 is highly important. A small value (X2=2.1) means permuting X2 has little effect — X2 contributes minimally. This ranking guides variable importance assessment."},
{id:182,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Evaluate overfitting risk in boosting",q:"A boosted tree model has 500 trees and achieves near-zero training RMSE but test RMSE is 3 times the training RMSE. What is the most appropriate remedy?",opts:["Add more trees — boosting always improves with more iterations","Apply early stopping — halt boosting before the model overfits training noise","Switch to random forest which cannot overfit","Increase the learning rate to allow each tree to make larger corrections"],ans:1,exp:"Boosting is more prone to overfitting than random forests because each tree actively tries to correct training errors. With too many trees the model fits training noise. Early stopping monitors validation error and halts when it begins to increase. Increasing learning rate worsens overfitting. Decreasing learning rate combined with early stopping is a common robust strategy."},
{id:183,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand hyperparameter effects in random forests",q:"In a random forest, increasing mtry (number of features considered at each split) from sqrt(p) to p (all features) changes the model in what way?",opts:["Forest becomes more randomized and variance decreases further","Forest converges to bagging — trees become more correlated reducing the variance-reduction benefit of aggregation","Forest becomes a single deep tree","Increasing mtry has no effect if number of trees is large enough"],ans:1,exp:"When all features are considered at every split (mtry=p), random forests reduce to bagging. The random feature restriction is essential — without it all trees will use the same dominant predictor at the top split, making trees highly correlated. Averaging correlated predictions does not reduce variance as effectively as averaging independent predictions."},
{id:184,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare boosting advantages and disadvantages vs random forests",q:"Boosting generally achieves higher predictive accuracy than random forests, but has an important disadvantage. What is that disadvantage?",opts:["Boosting cannot handle factor variables in any implementation","Boosting is more prone to overfitting because the sequential error-correction process can learn training noise if not constrained","Boosting requires more predictors than random forests","Boosting only works for binary classification targets"],ans:1,exp:"The manual explicitly states that boosting is more prone to overfitting compared to random forests. Boosting's sequential fitting — each tree targeting previous errors — can eventually fit training noise as the number of trees grows large. Random forests are more robust because independent trees average out individual overfitting. Learning rate (shrinkage) and early stopping mitigate boosting's overfitting tendency."},
{id:185,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand number of trees hyperparameter",q:"Why does increasing the number of trees in a random forest generally not cause overfitting?",opts:["More trees reduce both bias and variance simultaneously","Additional trees only contribute noise and cancel each other out after a large enough count","Random forests average predictions — adding more trees continues to reduce variance through averaging without systematically fitting noise unlike adding parameters to a GLM","More trees automatically apply more pruning"],ans:2,exp:"In random forests each tree is independently trained. Adding more trees adds more independent estimates to average, reducing variance through averaging. Unlike GLMs where adding predictors directly reduces training error and can overfit, adding trees does not change the model structure per observation — it just averages more estimates. However more trees increases computational time."},
{id:186,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply variable importance to feature selection",q:"A random forest is trained with 50 predictors. Variable importance shows 10 predictors account for 90% of total importance. How might this guide subsequent modeling?",opts:["All 50 predictors must be kept since the random forest used them all","The 10 most important predictors could be used in a simpler more interpretable GLM that captures most of the predictive signal","The 40 less important predictors should be swapped with new variables","Variable importance from random forests is unreliable and should be ignored for model building"],ans:1,exp:"Variable importance from random forests is a practical tool for feature selection and model simplification. If 10 predictors capture 90% of predictive information, a GLM or simpler model using just those 10 predictors may achieve nearly equivalent accuracy with much better interpretability. This is a common workflow: random forest for variable importance then GLM with selected features."},
{id:187,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Compare mtry default values",q:"A random forest classification model has p=16 predictors. The default value of mtry is approximately:",opts:["16 (all features)","8 (half of features)","4 (square root of 16)","2 (log of 16)"],ans:2,exp:"For random forest classification the default mtry is approximately the square root of p. With p=16 predictors: sqrt(16) = 4. For regression the default is p/3 approximately 5. The sqrt(p) heuristic balances randomness (reducing tree correlation) and informativeness (considering enough features to make meaningful splits)."},
{id:188,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate partial dependence plot interpretation",q:"A partial dependence plot (PDP) for a random forest shows that as miles_driven_per_year increases from 5000 to 30000, predicted premium rises by approximately 400. What does this represent?",opts:["The exact causal effect of miles on premium for individual policyholders","The average marginal effect of increasing miles driven averaging over all other predictor combinations in the training data","The coefficient of miles driven in a linear regression fitted to the same data","The range of predicted premiums across all observations with different mileage levels"],ans:1,exp:"Partial dependence plots show the marginal effect of a single predictor on model predictions by computing predictions at different values of that predictor while averaging over all other predictor values. The 400 increase represents the average effect across all policyholder profiles — not the effect for any specific individual."},
{id:189,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand OOB error estimate",q:"The OOB error in a random forest provides an estimate of test error. Why does this work without requiring a separate test set?",opts:["OOB error is always identical to test set error so a test set is unnecessary","For each observation predictions are made only by trees that did not use that observation for training — similar to cross-validation without requiring separate data","OOB error is calculated on the training set but adjusted for model complexity","OOB error averages predictions from all trees regardless of whether the observation was in the bootstrap sample"],ans:1,exp:"Each bootstrap sample contains approximately 63.2% of training observations. The remaining approximately 36.8% are OOB for that tree. For each training observation predictions are averaged only from trees where it was OOB — trees that never saw this observation during training. This produces an honest out-of-sample estimate without requiring a separate test set, similar in spirit to cross-validation."},
{id:190,topic:"Ensemble Methods",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare two variable importance metrics",q:"A random forest variable importance table shows two columns: %IncMSE (percent increase in MSE after permutation) and IncNodePurity (increase in node purity). Predictor X shows high %IncMSE but low IncNodePurity. How should this be interpreted?",opts:["X is important by one measure but not the other — the two metrics can disagree because they measure different aspects of variable importance","X should be automatically removed since one measure shows low importance","The metrics always agree so there must be a calculation error","The lower IncNodePurity means X causes less splitting and should be deprioritized in all cases"],ans:0,exp:"The two variable importance measures assess different aspects: %IncMSE (permutation importance) measures how much OOB accuracy degrades when X is permuted — a direct measure of predictive contribution. IncNodePurity (impurity importance) measures total reduction in node impurity attributed to X across all splits. They can disagree especially under correlated predictors. Using both metrics together provides a more complete picture of variable importance."},
{id:191,topic:"PCA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define PCA and its goal",q:"What is the primary goal of Principal Components Analysis (PCA)?",opts:["To predict a target variable using a linear combination of all predictors","To find a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset while retaining as much variance as possible","To identify which variables are most correlated with the target","To cluster observations into homogeneous groups based on all variables"],ans:1,exp:"PCA is an unsupervised method whose primary goal is dimensionality reduction — finding a lower-dimensional representation of a high-dimensional dataset while preserving maximum variance. It transforms original variables into uncorrelated principal components ordered by decreasing variance."},
{id:192,topic:"PCA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand the loading constraint in PCA",q:"For each principal component in PCA, the sum of squared loadings must equal 1. What is the purpose of this constraint?",opts:["It ensures that all loadings are positive","It ensures PCs are normalized — their variances (eigenvalues) are directly comparable and the components have unit length","It prevents two PCs from having identical loadings","It ensures loadings sum to zero for interpretability"],ans:1,exp:"The unit-norm constraint (sum of phi-j squared = 1) ensures each PC is normalized — it has a well-defined direction and magnitude. Without this constraint loadings could be arbitrarily scaled. The constraint makes eigenvalues comparable measures of variance and ensures PCs are uniquely defined up to sign flip."},
{id:193,topic:"PCA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Interpret PCA loadings",q:"PC1 has loadings (0.52, 0.50, -0.49, -0.53) for variables (savings, income, debt, expenses). How should PC1 be interpreted?",opts:["PC1 is dominated by savings since it has the highest loading","PC1 represents the contrast between financial assets (savings, income — positive loadings) and financial obligations (debt, expenses — negative loadings)","PC1 should be ignored because the loadings are mixed signs","PC1 is an average of all four variables since loadings are roughly equal in magnitude"],ans:1,exp:"When loadings have roughly equal magnitudes with mixed signs, the PC represents a contrast between positive-loading and negative-loading groups. Here savings and income (positive) contrast with debt and expenses (negative). A high PC1 score means high savings and income relative to debt and expenses — essentially a net financial health measure."},
{id:194,topic:"PCA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply orthogonality constraint to find missing loadings",q:"PC1 = (0.707, 0.707, 0.000) and PC2 = (a, b, 0.900). Given PCs are orthogonal, the constraint on a and b is:",opts:["a squared + b squared = 0.81","a + b = 0","0.707 times a + 0.707 times b = 0 which simplifies to a + b = 0","a = b = 0.316"],ans:2,exp:"Orthogonal PCs have loading vectors with dot product = 0. Dot product of PC1 and PC2: (0.707)(a) + (0.707)(b) + (0.000)(0.900) = 0. This gives 0.707(a+b) = 0 so a+b=0 meaning b=-a. Combined with unit norm: a squared + b squared + 0.900 squared = 1 giving 2 times a squared = 0.19 so a approximately 0.308 and b approximately -0.308."},
{id:195,topic:"PCA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Decide how many PCs to retain",q:"PCA on 8 standardized variables produces eigenvalues: 3.2, 1.8, 1.1, 0.8, 0.5, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1. Using the Kaiser criterion, how many PCs should be retained?",opts:["2 PCs","3 PCs","4 PCs","8 PCs"],ans:1,exp:"The Kaiser criterion retains PCs with eigenvalues greater than 1, since an eigenvalue > 1 means the PC explains more variance than a single standardized original variable. Eigenvalues > 1: 3.2, 1.8, 1.1. The fourth eigenvalue (0.8) is below 1. Therefore 3 PCs are retained."},
{id:196,topic:"PCA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand PCA preprocessing requirements",q:"Before applying PCA to a dataset with variables measured on different scales (age in years, income in thousands, number of children), what preprocessing step is strongly recommended?",opts:["Log transformation of all variables","Binarization of all numeric variables","Standardization (subtract mean divide by SD) so all variables contribute equally to distance-based calculations","Removal of all variables with variance below 1.0"],ans:2,exp:"PCA finds directions of maximum variance. Without standardization, variables with larger scales (income in thousands) would dominate PCs simply because of their measurement units. Standardizing ensures each variable contributes equally to the covariance structure. The manual explicitly states standardization is strongly recommended before PCA."},
{id:197,topic:"PCA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand sign flipping in PCA",q:"PCA loadings are unique up to a sign flip. If PC1 loadings are (0.6, 0.8, -0.1), which alternative set of loadings is equally valid?",opts:["(0.36, 0.64, 0.01) — the squared loadings","(-0.6, -0.8, 0.1) — every loading flipped","(0.8, 0.6, -0.1) — loadings reordered","(0.6, 0.8, 0.1) — only the negative loading flipped"],ans:1,exp:"The sign ambiguity in PCA means that for any PC, flipping the signs of ALL loadings (not just some) produces an equally valid solution. (-0.6, -0.8, 0.1) is the sign-flipped version of (0.6, 0.8, -0.1). Scores are also flipped correspondingly. The choice of sign affects directional interpretation but not the magnitude of the component or its predictive value in models."},
{id:198,topic:"PCA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply PCA output to feature creation",q:"An analyst performs PCA on 20 financial ratios and retains 4 PCs. The PC scores for each observation will be used as predictors in a GLM. What is the key advantage of using PC scores as predictors?",opts:["PCs guarantee better GLM predictions than using original ratios","PC scores are uncorrelated with each other eliminating multicollinearity among the 4 new predictors","PC scores are always between 0 and 1 satisfying GLM constraints","Using 4 PCs instead of 20 ratios reduces the training set size proportionally"],ans:1,exp:"By construction PCs are orthogonal (uncorrelated). Using PC scores as predictors in a GLM eliminates multicollinearity — a key concern when using 20 correlated financial ratios directly. This reduces the number of predictors from 20 to 4 (dimensionality reduction) and provides uncorrelated features. The tradeoff is reduced interpretability since PCs are linear combinations of original ratios."},
{id:199,topic:"PCA",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify that PCA is unsupervised",q:"PCA is classified as which type of statistical learning?",opts:["Supervised learning — uses a target variable to create optimal PCs","Unsupervised learning — identifies patterns in data without a target variable","Semi-supervised learning — uses the target when available","Reinforcement learning — optimizes PCs based on rewards"],ans:1,exp:"PCA is an unsupervised learning method — it analyzes the structure of predictor variables without any reference to a target variable. The PCs are constructed to maximize variance in the predictor space not to predict any outcome. The manual explicitly states PCA is an unsupervised learning method of analyzing data without a target variable."},
{id:200,topic:"PCA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand PC score calculation",q:"PC1 has loadings (0.6, -0.8) for variables X1 and X2. An observation has standardized values X1=1.5, X2=0.5. What is this observation's PC1 score?",opts:["0.5","0.50","0.9","0.1"],ans:1,exp:"PC score = sum of (loading times variable value) = (0.6)(1.5) + (-0.8)(0.5) = 0.90 - 0.40 = 0.50. PC scores are computed as the inner product of the loading vector and the standardized variable values. Note that PCA should be applied to standardized variables."},
{id:201,topic:"PCA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate proportion of variance explained",q:"Eight variables produce eigenvalues: 3.2, 1.8, 1.1, 0.8, 0.5, 0.3, 0.2, 0.1 (total=8.0). What proportion of total variance do the first 3 PCs explain?",opts:["37.5%","52.5%","76.25%","87.5%"],ans:2,exp:"For standardized variables, total variance = number of variables = 8 (each standardized variable has variance 1). Proportion explained by first 3 PCs = (3.2 + 1.8 + 1.1) / 8.0 = 6.1 / 8.0 = 0.7625 = 76.25%. The first 3 PCs capture 76.25% of all variance while reducing dimensionality from 8 to 3."},
{id:202,topic:"PCA",diff:"Hard",lo:"Understand PCA limitations for predictive modeling",q:"An analyst fits a GLM using the top 3 PCA components derived from 10 correlated predictors instead of the original 10. What is the main DISADVANTAGE of this approach?",opts:["The 3 PCs cannot be used as predictors in a GLM","PC scores are always correlated with each other creating multicollinearity","The PCs are constructed without reference to the target variable so they may not capture the most predictive variance — some predictive information may be lost in discarded PCs","GLMs with PCs as predictors cannot compute standard errors for coefficients"],ans:2,exp:"PCA maximizes variance explained in the predictor space not predictive value for the target. The components that explain most variance in predictors may not be the ones most associated with the target. The predictively relevant variance might be in the 4th or 5th PC rather than the top 3. This is a key limitation compared to supervised dimensionality reduction methods."},
{id:203,topic:"PCA",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand PCA for factor variables",q:"A dataset has 15 numeric variables and 3 factor variables. An analyst wants to apply PCA to all 18 variables. What must be done to the factor variables first?",opts:["Nothing — PCA handles all variable types automatically","Remove the factor variables — PCA cannot use non-numeric data","Binarize the factor variables (create dummy variables) so they are numeric before applying PCA","Convert factor variables to numeric by assigning integers 1,2,3"],ans:2,exp:"PCA is designed for numeric variables — it computes a covariance matrix requiring numeric inputs. Factor variables must be binarized (dummy encoded) first: each level gets its own 0/1 dummy variable. The resulting dummy variables are numeric and can be included in PCA. The SOA has used PCA with dummy variables in past exams, making it acceptable for PA purposes."},
{id:204,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define the goal of clustering",q:"What is the primary goal of clustering analysis?",opts:["To predict a target variable using all available predictors","To group similar observations together and separate dissimilar ones into different clusters","To reduce the number of predictors by combining correlated ones","To identify which observations are outliers in the dataset"],ans:1,exp:"Clustering is an unsupervised learning technique whose goal is to discover natural groupings in data — grouping similar observations together and separating dissimilar ones. There is no target variable; the algorithm identifies structure based on distances or similarities between observations."},
{id:205,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Easy",lo:"Describe the k-means algorithm",q:"What is the correct sequence of steps in the k-means clustering algorithm?",opts:["(1) Choose k, (2) randomly assign observations to clusters, (3) calculate centroids, (4) reassign to nearest centroid, (5) repeat steps 3-4 until stable","(1) Calculate all pairwise distances, (2) choose k, (3) merge closest clusters, (4) repeat until k clusters remain","(1) Choose k, (2) calculate the covariance matrix, (3) compute eigenvectors, (4) assign observations to PCs","(1) Assign all observations to cluster 1, (2) split into k groups, (3) recalculate means, (4) stop when SSE=0"],ans:0,exp:"The k-means algorithm: (1) randomly assign each observation to one of k clusters; (2) calculate each cluster's centroid (mean of all observations in the cluster); (3) reassign each observation to the nearest centroid; (4) repeat steps 2-3 until cluster assignments stop changing. The starting point is random assignment (or providing k random initial centroids)."},
{id:206,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define Euclidean distance in clustering",q:"In k-means clustering, Euclidean distance measures similarity. Two observations are (2, 4) and (5, 8) in 2D space. What is their Euclidean distance?",opts:["5","7","25","3"],ans:0,exp:"Euclidean distance = sqrt(sum of (xi minus yi) squared) = sqrt((5-2) squared + (8-4) squared) = sqrt(9+16) = sqrt(25) = 5. Larger Euclidean distance means more dissimilar observations. K-means assigns each observation to the cluster with the closest centroid, measured by Euclidean distance."},
{id:207,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain the elbow method for selecting k",q:"In k-means clustering, the elbow method plots proportion of variance explained against different values of k. How is the optimal k identified?",opts:["The value of k where proportion of variance explained first exceeds 90%","The value of k where the curve shows an elbow — adding more clusters yields diminishing returns in variance explained","The value of k equal to the square root of the number of observations","The smallest k for which all clusters have more than 10 observations"],ans:1,exp:"The elbow method plots the proportion of variance explained by the clustering against k. As k increases within-cluster variation decreases with diminishing returns. The elbow is the k value where the improvement in fit notably flattens — suggesting additional clusters beyond this point do not meaningfully improve clustering. The elbow provides a practical heuristic for choosing k."},
{id:208,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand why standardization is needed for clustering",q:"K-means clustering is applied to variables: age (range 18-90) and satisfaction score (range 1-5) without standardization. What problem will occur?",opts:["The algorithm cannot run because variables have different ranges","Age will dominate the distance calculations simply because its values are larger — the clustering will effectively ignore the satisfaction score","Satisfaction score will dominate because it has fewer possible values","The centroids will always converge to the overall dataset mean"],ans:1,exp:"K-means relies on Euclidean distance. Without standardization, age ranges 72 units while satisfaction ranges only 4 units. Age differences contribute (72 squared) = 5184 to squared distance while the full range of satisfaction contributes only (4 squared) = 16. Age completely dominates clustering. Standardizing ensures both variables contribute equally to the distance calculation."},
{id:209,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand hierarchical clustering and dendrogram",q:"In agglomerative hierarchical clustering, where does the process start and how does it proceed?",opts:["Start with all observations in one cluster; progressively split into smaller clusters","Start with each observation as its own cluster; iteratively fuse the two most similar clusters until all are in one","Start with k random cluster centers; reassign observations until stable","Start with the two most distant observations; build clusters outward from each"],ans:1,exp:"Agglomerative (bottom-up) hierarchical clustering starts with each observation as its own individual cluster. At each step the two clusters with the lowest inter-cluster dissimilarity are fused. This continues until all observations are in a single cluster. The resulting hierarchy is visualized as a dendrogram where the height of each fusion represents the dissimilarity at which it occurred."},
{id:210,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Compare linkage methods in hierarchical clustering",q:"Which linkage method defines inter-cluster dissimilarity as the LARGEST pairwise distance between observations in two clusters?",opts:["Single linkage","Complete linkage","Average linkage","Centroid linkage"],ans:1,exp:"Complete linkage uses the largest pairwise dissimilarity between observations in two clusters as the inter-cluster dissimilarity. This creates compact spherical clusters and is generally preferred. Single linkage uses the minimum (smallest) pairwise distance, average uses the mean, and centroid uses the distance between centroids."},
{id:211,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Hard",lo:"Compare k-means and hierarchical clustering",q:"An analyst needs to run cluster analysis but wants to determine the number of clusters after examining the results rather than specifying k in advance. Which method is more suitable?",opts:["K-means — the elbow method determines k automatically during the algorithm","Hierarchical clustering — a single run produces the full dendrogram at all cluster levels; the number of clusters is chosen afterward by cutting the dendrogram","K-means with k=1 — the algorithm will automatically find the optimal number","Both methods require specifying k before analysis"],ans:1,exp:"A key advantage of hierarchical clustering is that a single analysis produces results for all possible numbers of clusters simultaneously (the dendrogram). The analyst can choose the number of clusters after examining the dendrogram by deciding at what height to cut it. K-means requires specifying k before running, necessitating separate analyses for different k values."},
{id:212,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate single linkage chaining",q:"Single linkage hierarchical clustering is known for a chaining tendency. What does this mean and which linkage avoids it?",opts:["Single linkage tends to create clusters with equal numbers of observations; complete linkage avoids this","Single linkage can create long stringy clusters where distant observations are chained together through nearby intermediaries; complete and average linkage produce more compact clusters","Single linkage always produces the same results as k-means; complete produces different results","Single linkage cannot handle Euclidean distance; complete linkage can"],ans:1,exp:"Single linkage uses the minimum pairwise distance between clusters. A cluster can grow by attaching any observation close to any member — even if far from the cluster center. This creates elongated chains rather than compact spherical clusters. Complete linkage requires all members of a cluster to be relatively close to all members of the other cluster before fusion, producing more compact spherical clusters."},
{id:213,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand clustering as feature creation",q:"After k-means clustering assigns each observation to one of 4 clusters, the cluster assignment is used as a new predictor in a GLM. What type of variable is the cluster assignment?",opts:["A continuous variable with values 1, 2, 3, 4","A factor (categorical) variable with 4 levels representing different groups","A binary variable indicating cluster membership","A count variable recording how many times each observation was reassigned"],ans:1,exp:"The cluster assignment is a factor (categorical) variable with k levels. The integers 1, 2, 3, 4 are just labels for the clusters — they do not have natural ordering or spacing. In R the cluster assignment should be converted to a factor before being used in a GLM so the model creates dummy variables rather than treating clusters as a linear numeric sequence."},
{id:214,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply correlation-based distance in hierarchical clustering",q:"Correlation-based distance groups observations similar in their pattern of variation rather than absolute proximity. When would this be more appropriate than Euclidean distance?",opts:["When all variables are on the same scale","When two observations have identical relative patterns but differ in absolute magnitude — they follow the same pattern despite different levels","When observations are evenly distributed in all dimensions","When the number of clusters exceeds the square root of observations"],ans:1,exp:"Correlation-based distance = 1 minus correlation. Two observations with the same pattern (both high on the same variables, both low on others) but different magnitudes will have correlation approximately 1 and distance approximately 0. In genomics or finance, observations that rise and fall together are functionally similar even if their absolute levels differ. Euclidean distance would consider them dissimilar; correlation distance correctly identifies their pattern similarity."},
{id:215,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Explain inversions in hierarchical clustering",q:"An inversion in hierarchical clustering occurs when a fusion at a higher level has a lower dissimilarity than a fusion at a lower level. Which linkage is most prone to inversions?",opts:["Complete linkage","Average linkage","Single linkage","Centroid linkage"],ans:3,exp:"Centroid linkage computes inter-cluster dissimilarity as the distance between cluster centroids. When two clusters are merged, the new centroid is a weighted average of the two old centroids. This can produce a centroid closer to other cluster centroids than the merged clusters themselves were — creating an inversion. Inversions make the dendrogram difficult to interpret and are a known drawback of centroid linkage."},
{id:216,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify clustering as unsupervised learning",q:"Why is clustering classified as an unsupervised learning technique?",opts:["Because it uses bootstrap samples instead of the full training dataset","Because it operates without a target variable — it finds patterns solely from predictor variables","Because it cannot be validated using standard statistical tests","Because it requires no hyperparameters to be specified"],ans:1,exp:"Clustering is unsupervised because it analyzes data structure without any target variable. There is no correct answer to train towards — the algorithm discovers natural groupings based on similarity. This contrasts with supervised learning (GLM, decision trees) which explicitly uses a labelled target variable for model training."},
{id:217,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Hard",lo:"Determine clusters from a dendrogram",q:"A dendrogram is cut at height h=8. At this height 3 branches remain unmerged. How many clusters result?",opts:["8","3","7","The number of original observations still ungrouped"],ans:1,exp:"When a dendrogram is cut at a given height, the number of vertical lines crossed by the horizontal cut equals the number of clusters. If 3 branches remain unmerged at height h=8 (i.e., 3 subtrees exist below the cut), those 3 subtrees define 3 clusters. Each subtree represents a cluster of observations that were all fused together before reaching height 8."},
{id:218,topic:"Clustering",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply k-means with multiple initializations",q:"K-means clustering may converge to a local minimum depending on initial centroid placement. What practical strategy addresses this?",opts:["Always initialize centroids at cluster means from a previous run","Run the algorithm multiple times with different random initializations and select the solution with the lowest total within-cluster variation","Apply cross-validation to select the optimal initialization","Use hierarchical clustering output as the initialization for k-means"],ans:1,exp:"K-means is sensitive to initial centroid placement and may converge to a local minimum. Running the algorithm multiple times with different random initializations explores different starting points. The solution with the lowest total within-cluster variation (SSE) across all runs is selected. Most software packages including R's kmeans() have an nstart parameter controlling the number of random initializations."},
{id:219,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define descriptive analytics",q:"A bank reviews five years of loan default data to identify which customer segments had the highest default rates historically. This is an example of:",opts:["Predictive analytics — it builds a model to forecast future defaults","Prescriptive analytics — it recommends which segments should be declined","Descriptive analytics — it examines historical data to identify past patterns","Supervised learning — it trains a model on labelled data"],ans:2,exp:"Descriptive analytics focuses on studying the past to identify relationships and patterns. Reviewing historical default rates by segment to understand what happened is purely descriptive — no prediction or optimization is involved. The goal is understanding history not forecasting the future."},
{id:220,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define predictive analytics",q:"An insurer builds a GLM to estimate the probability that each existing policyholder will lapse in the next 12 months. This is an example of:",opts:["Descriptive analytics — it uses historical lapse data","Prescriptive analytics — it decides which policyholders to contact","Predictive analytics — it uses models to make forward-looking probability estimates","Unsupervised learning — it clusters policyholders by risk profile"],ans:2,exp:"Predictive analytics focuses on anticipating the future by using models to make accurate predictions. Building a GLM to predict future lapse probability is predictive analytics — it uses historical patterns to forecast a future outcome for each policyholder."},
{id:221,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Easy",lo:"Define prescriptive analytics",q:"Using predicted lapse probabilities, an insurer offers retention incentives to the top 10% highest-risk policyholders to maximize retention while staying within budget. This is:",opts:["Descriptive analytics — it describes which policyholders are at risk","Predictive analytics — it uses the model predictions directly","Prescriptive analytics — it uses predictions to recommend constrained optimal actions","Unsupervised learning — it groups policyholders into deciles"],ans:2,exp:"Prescriptive analytics focuses on the outcome of decisions — it uses model predictions to recommend or optimize actions given constraints. Deciding which policyholders to contact (based on predictions) while maximizing retention within a budget (constraint) is prescriptive analytics. Descriptive looked backward; predictive made predictions; prescriptive decides what to do."},
{id:222,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Evaluate whether predictive modeling is appropriate",q:"A new fintech startup wants to predict credit risk for borrowers in a market segment with no historical loan data. Which modeling condition is most severely violated?",opts:["The business issue is unclear","Relevant data is unavailable — without historical loan performance there is no training data to build a reliable model","The model cannot be monitored after deployment","Machine learning cannot be used for credit risk"],ans:1,exp:"The manual's checklist includes relevant data is available to address the issue. Without any historical loan data for this segment, there is nothing to train a model on. The model cannot learn patterns from data that does not exist. Alternatives might include borrowing from similar markets, using proxy data, or using expert judgment-based scorecards until sufficient data accumulates."},
{id:223,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Frame a business question for modeling",q:"We want to identify which auto policyholders are most likely to have an at-fault accident next year so we can adjust premiums at renewal. Which modeling approach does this most directly call for?",opts:["Descriptive analytics summarizing past accident rates by age group","A regression model predicting the exact number of future accidents per policyholder","A classification model predicting the binary probability of having at least one at-fault accident ranked by risk","K-means clustering to group policyholders by driving behavior"],ans:2,exp:"The business question asks for identification of high-risk policyholders — a classification and ranking task. A binary classification model predicting at-fault accident probability and ranking policyholders gives the insurer what's needed: a risk ranking for premium adjustment. Regression predicting count is less directly useful for binary identification. Clustering does not produce the needed probability ranking."},
{id:224,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Select appropriate evaluation metric based on business objectives",q:"A hospital readmission prevention program has limited budget. The cost of a missed high-risk patient (false negative) is much higher than contacting a low-risk patient unnecessarily (false positive). Which metric should guide model evaluation?",opts:["Accuracy — proportion of all predictions that are correct","Specificity — to maximize identification of true negatives","Sensitivity (recall) — to minimize false negatives and identify as many high-risk patients as possible","AUC — because it considers all possible cutoff values equally"],ans:2,exp:"When false negatives are much more costly than false positives, sensitivity (true positive rate) is the primary metric. Maximizing sensitivity means catching as many true high-risk patients as possible even if some low-risk patients are also flagged. The business context — cost of missed patient >> cost of unnecessary contact — directly maps to maximizing sensitivity."},
{id:225,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply ethical and regulatory constraints to predictor selection",q:"A GLM for auto insurance pricing achieves the highest AUC when it includes ethnicity as a predictor. An actuary recommends excluding it. Which justification is most appropriate?",opts:["Ethnicity has too many levels to be modeled effectively as a factor variable","Including ethnicity would violate fairness, anti-discrimination regulations, and ethical standards — regulatory and ethical constraints can override statistical performance","Ethnicity is likely to cause multicollinearity with other geographic variables","The GLM cannot handle factor variables with more than 10 levels"],ans:1,exp:"The PA exam explicitly recognizes that business, ethical, and regulatory constraints can override predictive performance. Using ethnicity as a pricing factor violates insurance discrimination laws in many jurisdictions and raises serious ethical concerns. Even if AUC improves, the predictor should be excluded. Not all statistically useful predictors should be included — this is a key insight the exam tests."},
{id:226,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Identify which analytics layer a specific activity represents",q:"An actuary: (1) reviews historical claims to understand frequency patterns by region; (2) fits a Poisson GLM predicting future claim frequency per policy; (3) uses predictions to set premiums maximizing expected profit subject to a 10% maximum rate increase rule. Match each step to its analytics type.",opts:["Step 1=Predictive, Step 2=Descriptive, Step 3=Prescriptive","Step 1=Descriptive, Step 2=Predictive, Step 3=Prescriptive","Step 1=Prescriptive, Step 2=Descriptive, Step 3=Predictive","Step 1=Descriptive, Step 2=Prescriptive, Step 3=Predictive"],ans:1,exp:"Step 1 examines historical data to understand past patterns — Descriptive analytics. Step 2 uses historical patterns in a model to predict future claim frequency — Predictive analytics. Step 3 uses predictions to make optimal decisions subject to constraints (maximize profit, max 10% increase) — Prescriptive analytics. This three-step workflow is the classic analytics hierarchy in actuarial practice."},
{id:227,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand KPI definition",q:"A key performance indicator (KPI) in the context of predictive modeling refers to:",opts:["The p-value threshold used for testing regression coefficients","Any measurement that summarizes the scenario of interest and can assess whether the business problem has been addressed","The number of predictors in the final model","The regularization penalty value selected by cross-validation"],ans:1,exp:"The manual defines a KPI as any measurement that summarizes the scenario of interest and can be used to assess whether the problem has been addressed. In a claims fraud project the KPI might be the false negative rate or dollar savings from fraud detected. KPIs translate the business problem into measurable outcomes the model should optimize or improve."},
{id:228,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate communication of model results",q:"After building a random forest with AUC=0.89, an actuary must present results to senior management with no statistical background. Which communication approach is most appropriate?",opts:["Present the full ROC curve and explain AUC=0.89 using the formula TP/(TP+FN)","Translate model performance into business metrics: the model identifies X% of future defaulters in the top 20% of risk scores enabling targeted intervention","Show the 500-tree average decision path as a flowchart","Recommend switching to logistic regression since GLMs are easier to explain"],ans:1,exp:"Communication to non-technical stakeholders should use business language and metrics. Saying our model identifies 70% of all future defaulters by flagging only the top 20% of accounts is far more meaningful than AUC=0.89 to a business audience. Translating model performance into business impact (dollars saved, cases caught, actions enabled) is essential for stakeholder buy-in."},
{id:229,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Easy",lo:"Understand the Exam PA format",q:"SOA Exam PA consists of approximately how many tasks and how long is the exam?",opts:["5 tasks, 2 hours","10 tasks, 3.5 hours","15 tasks, 4 hours","20 tasks, 5 hours"],ans:1,exp:"The manual states Exam PA has a duration of 3.5 hours carrying 70 points with about 10 tasks each potentially having subtasks. With 70 points over 3.5 hours the guideline is approximately 3 minutes per exam point."},
{id:230,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply the 3 minutes per point rule",q:"An Exam PA task is worth 5 points. Approximately how much time should be allocated to this task?",opts:["5 minutes","15 minutes","25 minutes","35 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"The manual's guideline is approximately 3 minutes per exam point (70 points over 3.5 hours = 210 minutes divided by 70 points = 3 minutes per point). For a 5-point task: 5 times 3 = 15 minutes. This time budget discipline is important — spending too long on early tasks leaves insufficient time for later ones."},
{id:231,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Identify types of exam tasks",q:"Which of the following is listed as a typical task type on Exam PA?",opts:["Proving mathematical theorems from first principles","Conceptual understanding: explaining statistical concepts","Designing new sampling protocols","Replicating actuarial pricing models from scratch"],ans:1,exp:"The manual lists three typical task types on Exam PA: (1) Conceptual Understanding — explaining statistical concepts, (2) Data Analysis — examining output and providing critiques, (3) Calculation — computing statistical quantities. The exam is applied and practical focusing on using statistical tools in business contexts not deriving theoretical proofs."},
{id:232,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Frame sensitivity-specificity tradeoffs for business decisions",q:"A medical screening test for a rare but treatable disease: low cutoff = high sensitivity / low specificity; high cutoff = low sensitivity / high specificity. If the disease is fatal when missed but treatment is cheap, which cutoff strategy is appropriate?",opts:["High cutoff — to minimize false positives and unnecessary treatments","Low cutoff — to maximize sensitivity and minimize fatal missed cases","Whichever cutoff maximizes AUC","The cutoff that maximizes overall accuracy"],ans:1,exp:"Business context determines optimal cutoff selection. Missing a fatal treatable disease (false negative) is catastrophic while unnecessary treatment (false positive) is merely costly. This asymmetry strongly favors sensitivity maximization. A low cutoff flags more patients (some unnecessarily) but misses fewer fatal cases. AUC and accuracy do not capture this cost asymmetry."},
{id:233,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply the full modeling checklist",q:"An actuary proposes a predictive model to forecast employee turnover. Which element of the before-modeling checklist is most critical to verify first?",opts:["Confirming the model can be monitored and updated","Verifying that the business issue is clearly defined and relevant data is available","Ensuring the model uses only non-parametric methods","Confirming that the model will never overfit"],ans:1,exp:"The manual presents a checklist for determining if predictive modeling is appropriate. Business issue is clear and relevant data is available to address the issue are foundational — without clarity on what you are solving and data to train on, no modeling can proceed meaningfully. All other checklist items build on these foundations."},
{id:234,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Evaluate model monitoring requirements",q:"After deploying a credit risk model, the bank discovers that economic conditions have shifted significantly — default rates have doubled across all segments. What does this imply for the deployed model?",opts:["The model is permanently invalid and should be replaced with a GLM","The model should be monitored for performance drift and likely retrained or recalibrated with recent data to reflect the new economic environment","No action is needed — models trained on historical data always perform well on future data","The model's AUC is guaranteed to drop below 0.5 in a shifting environment"],ans:1,exp:"Model monitoring is explicitly listed as a prerequisite in the PA manual's before-modeling checklist. Economic regime changes cause covariate shift — the relationship between predictors and target may change from training conditions. The model needs monitoring to detect performance degradation and recalibration or retraining with recent data to remain useful. This is a routine challenge in deployed predictive models."},
{id:235,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Apply analytics hierarchy to an actuarial workflow",q:"An actuarial team: (a) reviews claims trends by peril type over 10 years; (b) builds a GLM predicting expected loss ratio by policy; (c) uses GLM predictions to select policies for renewal and set differentiated rates. Match to analytics types.",opts:["(a)=Prescriptive, (b)=Predictive, (c)=Descriptive","(a)=Descriptive, (b)=Predictive, (c)=Prescriptive","(a)=Predictive, (b)=Descriptive, (c)=Prescriptive","(a)=Descriptive, (b)=Prescriptive, (c)=Predictive"],ans:1,exp:"(a) Reviewing historical trends = Descriptive analytics (looking backward at what happened). (b) Building a model to predict future loss ratios = Predictive analytics (using data to forecast). (c) Using predictions to make renewal and pricing decisions = Prescriptive analytics (using predictions to determine optimal actions). This three-step workflow is the standard actuarial application of the analytics hierarchy."},
{id:236,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand exam PA vs exam SRM",q:"Exam PA builds on Exam SRM. What is the key difference in focus between the two exams?",opts:["SRM covers more advanced models than PA","SRM emphasizes theoretical understanding; PA emphasizes applying theory to solve business problems","PA is taken before SRM in the SOA exam sequence","SRM covers GLMs while PA covers only decision trees"],ans:1,exp:"The manual explicitly states: the key difference between SRM and PA is the focus: SRM emphasizes theoretical understanding while PA emphasizes applying theory to solve business problems. PA requires not just knowing how models work but being able to use them to answer business questions, interpret outputs, and make recommendations in context."},
{id:237,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Identify exam PA task type from description",q:"An Exam PA task states: Critique the following output: The analyst applied MLR to a binary target variable. This is best classified as which task type?",opts:["Calculation","Conceptual Understanding","Data Analysis","Prediction"],ans:2,exp:"The task asks the student to examine model output and identify issues (applying MLR which requires continuous normally-distributed target to a binary target is inappropriate). This falls under Data Analysis: Examining output and providing critiques. Conceptual Understanding asks to explain concepts; Calculation asks to compute quantities. Critiquing outputs is the Data Analysis type."},
{id:238,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Medium",lo:"Understand business problem framing",q:"An insurance company wants to identify which auto policyholders are most likely to be unprofitable next year so underwriting criteria can be tightened. An analyst proposes two models: Model A — logistic regression predicting a binary unprofitable flag; Model B — Poisson GLM predicting expected claim counts. Which model better aligns with the business question?",opts:["Model B because predicting claim counts is always more informative than a binary outcome","Model A because the business question asks for a direct probability of an unprofitable outcome which drives the underwriting decision","Either model is equivalent since both use historical claims data","Model A is correct only if the unprofitable flag is perfectly balanced across classes"],ans:1,exp:"The business question asks for identification of unprofitable policyholders — a binary classification task. Model A directly predicts this probability which can be ranked to target the riskiest policyholders. Model B predicts claim frequency which is one input into profitability but does not directly answer whether the policyholder will be unprofitable overall. Aligning model choice to the business question is a core PA exam skill."},
{id:239,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Hard",lo:"Apply analytics type classification",q:"After building a claim severity model, an insurer uses predictions to set premiums that optimize the combined ratio subject to a constraint that no policyholder's premium increases by more than 20%. At which stage of the analytics hierarchy does this optimization sit?",opts:["Descriptive analytics because it summarizes historical claim data to set premiums","Predictive analytics because the model output is used to make forward-looking premium decisions","Prescriptive analytics because it uses model outputs to recommend an optimal action (premium setting) subject to business constraints","Supervised learning because the model was trained on labelled historical data"],ans:2,exp:"Prescriptive analytics uses the output of predictive models to recommend optimal decisions under constraints. Building and running the severity model is predictive analytics. Using those predictions to optimize the combined ratio subject to a maximum price increase cap — a constrained business decision — is prescriptive analytics. This hierarchy is explicitly tested in the PA exam."},
{id:240,topic:"Business Context",diff:"Easy",lo:"Identify Exam PA task types",q:"Which of the following is an example of a Calculation task on Exam PA?",opts:["Explain what the Gini index measures and how it is used in decision trees","Critique the following confusion matrix and identify if the model meets the project objective","Compute the Gini index for a node with 60 positives and 40 negatives out of 100 observations","Recommend whether to use a random forest or a GLM for this business problem"],ans:2,exp:"Calculation tasks on Exam PA require computing statistical quantities. Computing the Gini index = 1 minus (0.6 squared + 0.4 squared) = 1 minus 0.52 = 0.48 is a numerical calculation. Explaining the Gini index is Conceptual Understanding. Critiquing a confusion matrix is Data Analysis. Recommending a model is a combination of Conceptual Understanding and Data Analysis."}
];
